<SECOND>AM-Forest Fires, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0816,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yellowstone Road Reopened, Storm Sparks Idaho Fires</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with rain in Yellowstone, fires
in Montana and pilot killed in California; picking up 4th graf pvs
`Park officials.' SUBS 11th graf pvs `In Idaho' with 2 grafs to
include Montana fire and details of Idaho fire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Yellowstone National Park got its first significant rainfall since Memorial Day on Friday, and the rain and cooler temperatures aided firefighters battling a 40,000-acre fire. In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, the pilot of a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> plane was killed Friday when his plane crashed while surveying a fire in the <ORGANIZATION> Sequoia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> about 35 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, authorities said. Fires also burned in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. Yellowstone received about two hours of intermittent rainfall Friday. `` One short rain shower is not adequate to douse the fires. But it does help increase humidity in the air and it helps slow the fires down,'' said park spokeswoman <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Anzelmo </PERSON>. She said the temperature in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> cooled down Friday afternoon, the wind slowed and firefighters made some progress in their efforts to contain fires burning on nearly 200,000 acres of the park. Park officials on Friday morning reopened a road between <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Junction </LOCATION> and Old Faithful that had been closed Thursday because of the fire and smoke. The fire, pushed east by winds whipping at up to 40 mph Thursday, had crossed the road in several spots near <LOCATION> Nez </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Perce </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> as it grew by about 3,000 acres during the day. The fire's north edge was about 1 -LCB- miles south of the <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Junction </LOCATION> campground, which remained open, and wind was pushing the flames to the east into backcountry, <PERSON> Anzelmo </PERSON> said. The 20,260-acre Fan fire in the park's northwestern corner remained inside containment lines and burning had slowed on the Shoshone and Red fires, which had charred about 34,000 acres. Despite the fires, tourism in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> remains high, <PERSON> Anzelmo </PERSON> said. `` We are continuing to see a very busy park with campgrounds and hotels full each night,'' she said. `` But the last two days, there have been fairly smoky conditions in the park and the vicinity, so that has been difficult for everyone.'' In <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, cool, cloudy weather slowed a 2,800-acre fire burning in the <LOCATION> Elkhorn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> southeast of <PERSON> Helena </PERSON> Friday. Fire crews continued the slow work of building fire lines by hand in steep terrain, forest officials said. The cool weather also helped 125 firefighters battling an 8,000-acre grass and range fire southeast of <PERSON> Dillon </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, fire crews carved a break line between the raging 4,000 <LOCATION> Walker </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> fire and the southeastern town of <LOCATION> Inkom </LOCATION> on Friday. Residents from 16 rural homes were evacuated Thursday when flames whipped by 60 mph gusts swept over thousands of acres of sage, grass and groves of trees. The families stayed away from their homes Friday, and residents of 32 other homes were warned they might have to leave their homes. No structures were lost and no injuries were reported. Hundreds of firefighters were strung out across the southern part of the state against the worst of more than 75 fires started by lightning Thursday. `` We're snowed under here just trying to get people on fires,'' <ORGANIZATION> Challis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> said. `` We're going to be really thin on resources.'' In the <ORGANIZATION> Nez </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Perce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, where Thursday's storm sparked 20 new fires, some 180 firefighters tried to regain containment of the 1,000-acre Ruby Rapids fire after wind-driven flames broke through the containment line. Fire bosses hoped to recontain the fire by day's end and control it Saturday. Crews finally controlled the stubborn 1,500-acre Spring Canyon II fire in the <ORGANIZATION> Targhee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> near the <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> border Thursday night, and fire bosses were hoping to begin demobilization this weekend.
</TEXT>
