<HEAD>Woman Gives Birth In Fast-Food Restaurant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A vacationing couple stopped at a fast-food restaurant and left with a 5-pound, 4-ounce baby girl instead of the burger and fries they planned to purchase. <PERSON> Vanessa </PERSON> <PERSON> Megan </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, daughter of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Karla </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, was born Aug. 3 in a <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> restaurant in Magog, <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>, about 35 miles from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> border. The child, the <ORGANIZATION> Nelsons </ORGANIZATION>' third, was n't due until Sept. 1, <PERSON> Karla </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` It was the weirdest vacation I ever had in my life,'' her husband said. The couple was driving with their son <PERSON> Adam </PERSON>, 1, to the wedding of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>'s brother in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> when Mrs. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said she had a backache and asked her husband to stop at a restroom. They saw a McDonald's sign and decided to stop for a bite to eat at the same time. Mrs. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, 33, who said she experienced no other signs of labor, gave birth in the restroom and called for her husband. But he had taken <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> back to the car to wait for her. Mrs. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said she was trying to wash the baby in the restroom sink when a young girl entered and then went for help. Meanwhile, after several minutes of waiting in the car, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, 29, said he figured something was wrong and he and <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> returned to the restaurant. `` I saw a bunch of people by the bathroom ... and my wife holding a baby,'' he said. `` It was just a shock to me.'' A rescue squad took Mrs. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> and the baby to a hospital. As word of the unusual birth spread, the story was relayed in French on <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> television and radio and in local newspapers, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. The couple discovered through a television report translated for them that the owner-operator of the restaurant, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, was going to pay for their hospital and ambulance costs, which totaled almost $ 1,700, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> also paid for some baby clothes, diapers and an infant car seat, according to <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Caron </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>'s restaurants. That was good news for the couple because they have no health insurance. `` We would have paid so much a month like we do all our other bills,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> is a cook at the Downtowner in <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, and his wife is a hostess at a <PERSON> Marc </PERSON>'s Big Boy, where she returned to work Thursday.
</TEXT>
