<FIRST>r a PM-EconomyGlance     08-12 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Glance,0487</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Rising Interest Rates Affecting Markets</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 At a glance, these are among the latest economic developments:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PRIME RATE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Several major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks on Thursday raised their prime rate a half percentage point to 10 percent, just two days after the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> boosted its discount rate to 6.5 percent from 6 percent to stave off inflation. The increase brings the prime rate to its highest level since June 18, 1985, when it was lowered to 9.5 percent from 10 percent. It was the third time this year that banks have raised the prime, used to calculate a range of fixed and adjustable rate corporate and consumer loans.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RETAIL SALES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Retail sales climbed 0.5 percent in July, the third consecutive monthly increase. Sales increased $ 632 million to a seasonally adjusted $ 134.0 billion, but economists say rising interest rates threaten to dampen even this modest growth in the months ahead. The rise followed increases of 0.4 percent in June and 0.8 percent in May.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CROP REPORT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has reported that drought and high temperatures have shriveled the harvest of the nation's No. 1 crop, corn, to an estimated 4.48 billion bushels, down 37 percent from 7.06 billion bushels harvested in 1987. The drought will cause consumer food prices to go up an average 3 percent to 5 percent from 1987. Before the heat and dry weather, <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> had expected a 1988 food price hike of 2 percent to 4 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>STOCK MARKET</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices hovered in a narrow range Thursday, struggling to stabilize after the market's recent steep decline. Analysts said the market's drop over the past week had pushed prices down to levels where they attracted some buyers. But they also said widespread concern persisted over the recent rise in interest rates. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had fallen nearly 00 points over the five previous sessions, on Thursday rose 5.16 to 2,039.30.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HOUSING ACTIVITY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> reported home prices soared on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> in the April-June period, propelled by that region's booming economy, while prices lagged in depressed oil areas. The median price of existing single-family homes jumped to $ 204,000 in the <LOCATION> Anaheim-Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ana </LOCATION> area of <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, a 20.1 percent increase when compared with the second quarter of 1987. <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, with an appreciation rate of 19.1 percent, ranked second in the nation and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, with an increase of 15.5 percent, was third. The steepest declines from a year ago were in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where the median resale price fell 12.7 percent to $ 56,900. Nationally, prices rose 3.4 percent to a median of $ 88,900, meaning half of the houses sold for more and half for less.
</TEXT>
