<HEAD>Israel Eyes Export Market For The Birds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has begun breeding pigeons in a bid to boost the popularity of the much-maligned bird, a poor man's poultry considered a delicacy during biblical times The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> recently opened four pigeon nurseries housing 800 pairs of the birds in the <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Jerusalem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. Pigeon meat, more tender and pungent than chicken, was a favored delicacy during the time of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> and around 500 B.C., when poor people sacrificed the bird at Jewish temples. Pigeon meat has long been popular in <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> households, where many families raise the birds to vary their menu and as a cheap alternative to poultry. <PERSON> Zvi </PERSON> <PERSON> Karchi </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s research and development department, said he hoped to popularize the bird in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, where poultry is a dietary staple and Arab-style food is common. The newspaper also quoted <PERSON> Karchi </PERSON> as saying he expected <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to successfully compete with pigeon exporters like the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>.
