 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> has won the 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Jawaharlal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nehru </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Award </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Understanding </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> ambassador announced. The prize has been awarded annually since 1965 for outstanding contributions to international understanding, said Ambassador C.R. Gharekahn on Thursday. He said it reflects general achievements, but he specifically mentioned the secretary-general's role in negotiating a cease-fire between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The truce is to take effect Aug. 20. The award includes a cash prize of about $ 110,000. A jury of Indian officials selects the winner. The ambassador said <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> had agreed to come to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> for presentation of the prize, but a date had not been set. The award is named after <PERSON> Nehru </PERSON>, post-colonial <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s first prime minister. Previous winners include former <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General U Thant, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> civil rights leader <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, missionary <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON>, Dr. <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> <PERSON> Salk </PERSON> who developed a polio vaccine, South African activist <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, Indian leader <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, and Swedish Prime Minister <PERSON> Olof </PERSON> <PERSON> Palme </PERSON>.
