<SECOND>PM-Marcos-Mother,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos' Mother Unburied Three Months After Her Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATAC, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than three months after her death, the body of <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' mother is still unburied as her son's dwindling followers maintain a wake in hopes the government will allow him to come home. But civic leaders say that even here in `` <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> country,'' many believe the time has come to place the body of <PERSON> Josefa </PERSON> <PERSON> Edralin-Marcos </PERSON> in the marble tomb prepared for her in the family cemetery in a swamp on the eastern edge of this town. Mrs. <PERSON> Edralin-Marcos </PERSON> died May 4 at age 95, and her body was transferred the following month from <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> to the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> ancestral home in <LOCATION> Batac </LOCATION>, a town of about 50,000 people about 240 miles to the north. Family members and <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> supporters say no date for the burial will be set until President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> allows her deposed predecessor to return or until <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> orders the interment. The body has been embalmed at least twice, and <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> family mortician <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Malabed </PERSON> said the remains could remain unburied until the end of the year. The former president has lived in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> since a civilian-military uprising toppled his 20-year administration in 1986. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has refused to allow him back for security reasons. `` To be frank with you, we have not been able to set a definite date,'' said <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' sister <PERSON> Fortuna </PERSON> <PERSON> Barba </PERSON>, who attends daily prayer services before the open coffin in the family home. The mansion is now a museum. Pictures of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>, hang from the walls alongside banners such as: `` God's will, I'll return to save my nation and people from communism.'' `` We're still hoping, perhaps against hope, that the situation will change and something good may come out of it,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Barba </PERSON> said. Whatever sympathy <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> may have hoped to generate by his appeal to come home appears to have dissipated in the months following his mother's death. Filipino newspapers rarely mention the ongoing wake. In a rare exception, The <ORGANIZATION> Manila </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> recently suggested an epitaph: `` Here lies <PERSON> Dona </PERSON> <PERSON> Josefa </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, died at age 95, buried at age 96.'' <PERSON> Rodolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Farinas </PERSON>, provincial governor of <ORGANIZATION> Ilocos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Norte </ORGANIZATION> and a close friend of the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> family, said if <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> believes he has no chance to return, `` he should give the word that his mother should be laid to rest.'' The Rev. <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Abaya </PERSON>, a Roman Catholic priest, said the arrival of Mrs. <PERSON> Edralin-Marcos </PERSON>' body generated considerable enthusiasm in <LOCATION> Batac </LOCATION> because many believed <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was returning for the funeral. Pro-Marcos politicians erected red, white and blue signs in <LOCATION> Batac </LOCATION> and in neighboring towns welcoming the former president to his provincial stronghold. But as the weeks dragged on without the Apo, or Grand Old Man, both the signs and the enthusiasm are fading. Under a rotation system, residents take turns attending daily prayers before the casket. But attendance has dwindled from hundreds to a few dozens each day. `` The feeling seems to be that the woman has suffered enough and should be laid to rest,'' <PERSON> Abaya </PERSON> said. Vice Mayor <PERSON> Rodolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Yadao </PERSON>, a member of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> party, said townspeople were still eager for <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to return. <PERSON> Yadao </PERSON> said, however, that townspeople were losing patience with his nearly fanatical supporters from <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> who came here for the wake. `` We have to provide for them,'' <PERSON> Yadao </PERSON> said. `` Sometimes, they are quarelling with themselves. She should be buried now. That is our tradition.'' He was referring to the practice of burying people within nine days of death. At <LOCATION> Laoag </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, about six miles north, the military has placed metal barricades, mounds of gravel and six concrete abutments on the runway, shortening it by 1,200 yards to prevent <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> from slipping in on a charter flight from abroad. Some <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> supporters vow to continue the wake indefinitely until their leader returns. But asked if the family were prepared for an indefinite standoff, Mrs. <PERSON> Barba </PERSON> replied: `` Well, I suppose if there is no hope, I'll get a call from him one day telling me to go ahead with it.''
