<FIRST>r w PM-FBIRacism     08-12 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FBI Racism,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Major Parts of FBI Agent's Racial Harassment Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Major portions of a black <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent's racial harassment lawsuit against the government have been dismissed as technically defective, but the plaintiff's lawyer says the ruling ultimately will be a victory. Attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kairys </PERSON> said many of the legal flaws found by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> in agent <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON>'s complaint can be corrected and the case will go forward. The <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> lawyer said <PERSON> Richey </PERSON>'s order Thursday leaves the essential element of the case intact. `` He has upheld our ability to get personal damages against the individual wrongdoers,'' <PERSON> Kairys </PERSON> said. `` This is very important and was not a matter of certainty when we started this.'' In a highly technical opinion, <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> dismissed `` without prejudice'' most of the claims against 21 white <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents, whom <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON> contends engaged in a three-year campaign of harassment that included anonymous telephone calls, obscene mail and death threats. <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON> also contends agents threatened his white wife with sexual assault. The `` without prejudice'' proviso <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> attached to most of the dismissals gives <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON> an opportunity to file a new complaint to try to correct the legal defects identified by the judge. <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> said the complaint, while raising `` repugnant and chilling'' allegations, `` contains defects in both pleading and legal theory that constrain the court to dismiss many of the plaintiff's claims.'' The judge, however, refused to dismiss common-law claims against three white <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents _ <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Dillon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Veach </PERSON> _ whom <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON> said spearheaded harassment when he worked in that city. <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> also refused to dismiss <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON>'s claim that his civil rights were violated under Title VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act. But he dismissed 21 <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents and top officials as defendants in that claim, saying only the attorney general could be sued as head of <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON>'s agency. He also found that many of <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON>'s claims against individual agents, particularly supervisors who allegedly ignored the racial harassment complaints, were pre-empted under other statutes by the Title VII claim. <PERSON> Kairys </PERSON> chose to hail <PERSON> Richey </PERSON>'s decision to preserve the civil rights claim, saying it was the vehicle for the overall harassment and discrimination complaint. `` The individuals, at least temporarily, some of them, are off the hook, but the judge has clearly said the only problem is he does n't want Title VII and allegations about the individuals to be merged,'' <PERSON> Kairys </PERSON> said. `` That is just a matter of filing an amended complaint which separates them,'' he said. But <PERSON> Kairys </PERSON> conceded he will have difficulty sustaining claims against the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> supervisors and managers that <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON> claims deliberately ignored his complaints. <PERSON> Kairys </PERSON> said he was gratified by <PERSON> Richey </PERSON>'s stern warning to the defendants to stop referring to the racial harassment incidents as `` pranks.'' `` This utter lack of sensitivity is almost as disturbing as the alleged acts themselves,'' <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> said, adding that `` the court hereby warns defendants that a modicum of decency is expected for all those who file pleadings in this court.'' <PERSON> Kairys </PERSON> said, `` The judge really recognized how inappropriate it has been for the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> and their lawyers to fail to acknowledge that something other than pranks occurred here.'' The judge also dismissed altogether complaints against three agents arising from alleged racial harassment incidents when <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON> worked in the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, field office in 1983 and 1984. <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> found that the statute of limitations had expired on those claims. The <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> upheld many of <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON>'s complaints about harassment in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION>'s investigation of the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> incidents was suspended after the suit was filed <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON>, 38, now works in the bureau's <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> office. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who admitted during an internal investigation that he forged <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON>'s signature on an application for `` death and dismemberment'' insurance, is the subject of a grand jury investigation. The insurance policy was sent to <PERSON> Rochon </PERSON>'s home as part of what <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> called an attempt to get `` retribution'' for the black agent's complaints of racial harassment. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> was suspended for two weeks without pay but fellow white agents took a collection to pay his salary, according to statements made in court.
