<HEAD>Feds Checking Near-Collision Over Atlantic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal investigators are trying to determine why a jetliner was flying at the wrong altitude over the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and almost collided with another jetliner earlier this week. Word of the incident emerged Thursday when the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said it was investigating a report filed by one of the pilots, who estimated the two aircraft came within 200 to 300 feet of each other. The incident last Monday occurred about 700 miles east of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and involved <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> L-1011 jetliners flown by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> charter airline, and LuftTransport, a West German charter carrier, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Capt. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Reb </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> pilot, said he was talking to his co-pilot when he suddenly saw the other plane through a side window of the cockpit. He immediately lowered the nose of his plane and descended 1,000 feet, according to an airline spokesman. At the time, both jets were cruising at about 550 miles per hour at 35,000 feet with <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> Flight 665 flying directly west and the LuftTransport Flight 410 heading southwest and converging, according to government and airline officials. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said the LuftTransport plane should have been flying at 31,000 feet. Flight 665 with 250 passengers and 12 crew members was bound from <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> John </LOCATION> <LOCATION> F. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Recker </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, which is based in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>. It could not immediately be determined how many people were aboard the other plane, but such European charter flights normally are heavily booked during the summer months, according to aviation experts. The LuftTransport jet was bound from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Cancun </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The airspace over the ocean where the incident occurred is not covered by radar, but jetliners are assigned specific routes, speed and altitude by controllers at <LOCATION> Gander </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION>, and at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. According to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>, the West German plane had just left airspace controlled by the Gander controllers and entered airspace controlled by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> control center when the incident occurred. `` The -LRB- German -RRB- plane should have descended to 31,000 feet before it entered <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> airspace,'' said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON>. <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said preliminary reports indicate that both planes were flying the proper route but that `` it looks like a case of the wrong altitude'' on the part of the LuftTransport plane. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> investigators planned to interview controllers at both <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and Gander to determine whether the LuftTransport pilot was assigned the wrong altitude. <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said both pilots saw the other aircraft. `` It was close and it's kind of frightening,'' said <PERSON> Recker </PERSON>. He said no one aboard the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> plane was injured during the incident and that it was over before the passengers were aware of anything unusual. LuftTransport is based in <LOCATION> Dusseldorf </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>.
