<SECOND>PM-Medical Waste-Congress,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Moves On Medical Waste Issue Before Returning Home For
Recess</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawmakers took several steps to fight the ocean dumping of medical waste before heading back to districts where waves of the infectious debris have marred the summer for <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> resort towns and vacationers. A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee voted Thursday to stiffen federal penalties for illegal dumping as <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> prepared to leave town for the August recess, and other lawmakers drafted separate measures to track hospital debris and make violators financially liable for lost revenue to coastal communities. Meanwhile, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> injected the topic into presidential politics, calling on Attorney General-designate <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> to determine if the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> can be used to strengthen government anti-pollution enforcement. `` Our ocean should not be a dumping ground,'' the vice president said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called medical waste floating up on <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> beaches a `` national disgrace'' and termed the situation `` dangerous,'' just two days after the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that `` guidance and education'' _ not new rules on disposal of medical waste _ were the answer. <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> officials on Tuesday had told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel that they believe the debris does not pose a major health threat. In <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on crime approved legislation that would create a specific federal law against medical waste dumping, carrying penalties up to five years in prison, $ 250,000 in fines and forfeiture of assets such as ships used in illegal dumping. Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, the subcommittee chairman and sponsor of the bill, said current laws do not address medical waste dumping specifically and do not cover dumping in all circumstances. `` Even if they are apprehended, the current penalties amount to little more than a slap on the wrist,'' said <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, who represents <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> shore communities. `` By making illegal medical waste disposal a federal criminal offense, we will be raising the stakes considerably.'' Rep. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Studds </PERSON>, D-Mass., who represents resort towns on <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Martha </PERSON>'s Vineyard and <LOCATION> Nantucket </LOCATION>, introduced legislation similar to <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>' bill, but also including a liability provision Under the <PERSON> Studds </PERSON> measure, state and local governments would be able to recover lost tax revenues from violators. In addition, coastal homeowners could recover for damaged property and fishermen and tourist-related businesses could recover for lost business due to medical waste. `` While the medical risk associated with this debris is fairly low, it is intolerable that garbage finds its way into the ocean and onto our shores,'' said <PERSON> Studds </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> and Fisheries subcommittee on fisheries and the environment. Rep. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, D-Conn., filed legislation calling for a manifest system to track medical waste produced in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last week passed a similar pilot program proposal for <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. The federal government has no mandatory tracking system, and <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials have said they will continue with voluntary efforts instead of imposing regulations. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Denit </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s office of solid waste, said the agency would use `` education and guidance'' to discourage companies from dumping medical waste at sea.
