<HEAD>Bush Has Cash To Spare For His Small Share Of Convention Cost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> comes to the Republican convention with more money than anticipated after rationing everything from plane travel to office supplies to keep from going over the federal cap on spending, his staff says. Although <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> does n't have to worry about paying for the multimillion-dollar Superdome convention, he does have to pay related campaign costs such as housing and staff payroll. To make those ends meet, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been forced to keep a tight rein on campaign spending over the past few months to stay under the $ 23 million primary spending limit that is set for presidential campaigns. Candidates are allowed more than $ 4 million on top of that for fund-raising costs, which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also raised and spent. Entering the last six weeks of the campaign, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> began July with less than $ 1 million to go before hitting the limit. He has only to make it through his nomination Wednesday night to get $ 46 million from the federal treasury for his fall race against Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Until then, his campaign is ruled by the primary limit. `` We've been penny-pinchers all along and we're very careful with our finances,' ` said finance spokeswoman Ede Holiday, who added, `` Obviously we are very close to our spending limit.'' She declined to say how close. Four Democratic state chairmen have accused <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> of overspending the limit and filed a complaint with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> last week. Holiday said the campaign kept a tight budget that, as planned, will last just through the convention. `` We have plenty of money to do what we want to do at the convention,'' she said. Holiday would not say how much the campaign was spending for convention activity, but said the belt-tightening in recent weeks has l