<HEAD>Bush and Wright Tangle Over Investigation, Insults</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> locked horns at a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> dinner party after <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said he was `` surprised and hurt'' that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had called for a special prosecutor to investigate ethics charges against him. Aides to the two officials described the Wednesday night episode after insisting on anonymity. They said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> retorted by complaining about the Democratic convention, where speakers referred to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as `` a toothache of a man'' and taunted `` Where was <PERSON> George </PERSON>?'' in suggesting he was an invisible vice president. The aides provided differing descriptions of the intensity of the exchange, which occurred at the annual House Gym Dinner given for members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> who use the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> athletic facilities. `` It was a polite, private discussion, not a heated exchange, no profanities,'' said the <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> aide. In contrast, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aide said: `` It was quite a heated exchange with a lot of witnesses. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> started screaming and yelling that he -LRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> -RRB- had impugned his -LRB- <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s -RRB- integrity.'' The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aide said <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> used profanities. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> called <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Thursday, but not to apologize, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s aide said The aide said <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> `` reassured him there was no personal animosity of any sort,'' and the two agreed they could `` make contributions by maintaining a high standard in their personal relationship.'' <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Tate </PERSON>, the campaign press secretary to the vice president, said, `` <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> 