<FIRST>r i PM-Burma-Analysis     08-12 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma-Analysis,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Clear Indication Of How Burma Revolt Will End</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Those who follow the rapidly moving events are uncertain of the outcome in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, where unarmed citizens are angry enough to confront rifles and the government is willing to shoot them down. Diplomats and other observers sketch a variety of finales to the drama that began with President <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>'s accession to power late last month and has progressed through increasing levels of popular protest and violence. Security forces initially were restrained and disciplined, but soldiers opened fire Tuesday on thousands of demonstrators in the streets of <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. Official reports say protest has spread to virtually every town and city in the the <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> nation of 38 million people. High school students in their mid-teens were the vanguard but witnesses say <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks, workers and ordinary townspeople have joined the mass denunciation of 26 years of authoritarian rule and economic deprivation. These are some of the results foreseen by diplomats in scenarios by diplomats in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>: _ Continued ruthless suppression of all protest by <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> and a loyal army until all opponents are rooted out or cowed into the passivity that characterized the political scene until recent events. _ The ouster of <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> by former strongman <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON>, who overthrew the democracy in 1962. He formally retired from political life last month, but some believe he still pulls the strings. _ An intensified and bloody uprising that would compel the army, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s most powerful institution, to overthrow the government and install a more moderate leadership. Unlike the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, where mass popular protest achieved greater political freedom, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> has no prominent personalities advocating democracy who could lead the growing but diffuse opposition. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON>, the most outspoken critic of the system, is 70 and retired from politics after falling out with Ne Win in the early 1960s. <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> has jailed the former army officer, a relative liberal. Protesters seem to illustrate this dearth of political alternatives by resurrecting old symbols and the images of leaders long dead. <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> marchers carry portraits of <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON>, the dashing fighter for <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> independence who was assassinated in 1947, and wave the peacock flag of days when <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> struggled against its British colonial masters. Like the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> under <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> has a strong military in which increasing disaffection is reported. Some diplomats speculate that elements of the army, as in the `` people power'' revolution that ousted <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, could provide the muscle to bring down <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>, a former general. The military has been <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s privileged class since Ne Win seized power, however. Retired or active military officers currently hold all but two Cabinet positions, and even the rank and file has privileges civilians do not enjoy. Ne Win assiduously built, or bought, the loyalty of a generation and more of army officers. Although his proclaimed ideology has been a mix of socialist economics, Buddhism and isolationism, political control has rested with the military and the army-dominated government political party. `` I find it hard to believe such a man steeped in power since 1962 giving it all up in one fell swoop. Something smells here,'' said a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat based in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> who spoke on the condition he not be identified. He added, however, that if <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON> returned the question remained whether the people now would accept `` the lesser of two evils'' even if he pursued urgently needed economic reforms. Some protesters still call the government the `` Ne Win regime'' and demand restoration of democracy. Marchers applauded loudly this week when passing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. Others say they are fighting for socialism minus <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>, who is widely hated for ruthlessly suppressing dissent since the 1960s. `` The young people have n't known anything in their lives but this system,'' a Burmese intellectual said recently. `` They do n't know exactly what they want or how to get it. Many Westerners arriving from <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> say Burmese from many walks seem certain of one thing: They have had enough of leaders who provide neither freedom nor rice.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> is <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> bureau chief of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> and has reported on and from <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> for a decade.
</TEXT>
