<SECOND>BC-Thornburgh-Thumbnail,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Thornburgh-Nominees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a sketch of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, confirmed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to succeed <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> as attorney general: AGE: 56. FAMILY: The son of an engineer and grandson of a university professor, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> is married to the former <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Judson </PERSON>, a schoolteacher. His first wife, also named <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, was killed in an automobile accident in 1960 that left the youngest of his three sons brain-damaged. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> now has a fourth son by his second wife, whom he married in 1963. EDUCATION: He earned a civil engineering degree from <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1954. He returned to his native <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> and earned a law degree from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in 1957. JOB HISTORY: He was appointed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney for western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> in 1969. As a prosecutor, his targets included a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> customs agent, a county sheriff and a former <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> congressman, <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> Whalley </PERSON>, who was convicted in a kickback case. In 1975, he was appointed by President Ford as assistant attorney general in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s criminal division. In 1978, the Republican <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> defeated former <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Flaherty </PERSON> for governor. He ran on a platform of cleaning up corruption in the Democratic administration of then-Gov. <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapp </PERSON>, a Democrat. He was re-elected in 1982, narrowly defeating former congressman <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ertel </PERSON> during a recession that made it difficult for incumbent <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> candidates. Barred by law from seeking a third term, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> left <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> at the end of 1986 to head the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Politics </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION>. POSITIONS AS GOVERNOR: <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s budget proposals held spending increases to less than the rate of inflation for eight straight years. He championed a controversial welfare reform law that limited cash benefits to three months a year for an estimated 68,000 people considered `` able-bodied.'' A sampling of his positions: _ On abortion, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> has a mixed record In December 1981, he vetoed an Abortion Control Act, saying he objected to sections that said life started at conception, that mandated a 24-hour waiting period, and that would have established criminal penalties for doctors who broke the law. On June 11, 1982, however, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> signed a watered-down version of the abortion bill, which required doctors to notify women about the risks of abortion and the availability of medical assistance for prenatal care and childbirth. Portions of the law were later struck down by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. _ On capital punishment, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said during both terms in office that he favored the death penalty for certain murders and for persons convicted of killing police officers and prison guards During his first term, the death penalty was reinstated in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. During his second term, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> signed warrants setting execution dates for several convicted murderers. Appeals courts granted stays in each case. _ On gun control, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said while campaigning for his first term that he opposed further government regulation of the sale or purchase of firearms Subsequent public statements on this issue could not be found. While governor, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> signed a bill setting a mandatory five-year sentence for any person convicted of using a gun during a crime.
</TEXT>
