sday morning session before the delegates get down to the work of dealing with reports from the convention's committees New Jersey Gov. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> will deliver the convention's keynote address Tuesday night, followed at the podium by former President <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday night, the delegates will give their presidential nomination to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, following a nominating speech by Sen. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Among the six seconding speakers are <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> football Coach <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Paterno </PERSON>, Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Jeb </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the vice president's son. Also on the list are Republican activist <PERSON> Ninfa </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, who says she plans to speak Spanish during her remarks, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Councilwoman <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maritime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Chao </PERSON>. On Thursday night, the delegates will pick a vice presidential nominee and hear the acceptance speeches by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his running mate before adjourning.
