<SECOND>PM-Gulf-Rebels,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peace Bad News For Rebels In Iraq, Iran</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dawn of peace in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war is likely to be a sunset for the hopes of rebels in each country, diplomats say. The cease-fire announced Monday may close crucial border sanctuaries used by the Kurdish rebels fighting <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and the leftist peoples' Mujahedeen seeking to topple <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>. That can only be bad news for Kurdish rebel leader <PERSON> Jalal </PERSON> <PERSON> Talabani </PERSON>, who declared in an April interview with <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> magazine: `` We can no longer live with -LRB- <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> President -RRB- <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> in the same country ... now it's either him or us.'' The cease-fire will take effect Aug. 20, and 350 <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> observers are to be in place along the 730-mile border within a week. That gives both countries a chance to concentrate on eliminating their rebels. `` I do n't think the Iraqis are going to be anything other than merciless'' toward the Kurdish rebels, said a Western diplomat in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Talabani </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kurdistan </ORGANIZATION>, fighting for a Kurdish republic, scored a series of military successes against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> late last year in alliance with Iranian forces. But their fortunes faded as <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s army appeared to crumble this year, and diplomats say <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> largely has squashed the Kurdish forces. Witnesses said <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has tried to rob the rebels of base areas by bulldozing dozens of villages in mountainous northern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, where about 2.5 million Kurds live. `` It's just one destroyed village after another,'' said a diplomat who has toured the area. Kurds from different villages have been moved to newly built towns of gray concrete houses _ breaking the tight social solidarity of village life that rebels often used for protection. `` Kurds will continue to be Kurds ... but the village way of life is a thing of the past,'' said the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat, who spoke on condition of not being identified further. A 1975 Iraq-Iran treaty closed the border to rebels in each country, helping quell Kurdish dissidence at that time. But <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s later support of Kurdish guerrilla action was one of the fuses that led to full explosion of the war in September 1980 <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in the past also supported Kurdish dissidents inside <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, but its main aid during the war went to the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khalq </ORGANIZATION>, which moved to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> after its leaders were expelled from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1986. The Mujahedeen-led <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> made a series of raids into Iranian territory this year. The latest drove 60 miles into <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and briefly captured two cities. Military observers said there is evidence that Iraqi forces aided the Iranian rebel operations, an allegation <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and the rebels denied. But a well-placed Iraqi source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said his government would almost surely block the border to the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> as part of any cease-fire. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khalq </ORGANIZATION> being based in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> does have a lot to do with the conflict,'' he noted. `` No doubt any peace settlement will mean the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khalq </ORGANIZATION> wo n't operate from Iraqi soil,'' said a European diplomat. <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Riza </PERSON> <PERSON> Jafer </PERSON> <PERSON> Zada </PERSON> refused to say whether the organization would move its battle entirely within <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. But he insisted that closing the border would not stop the rebellion against <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>. `` We have tremendous support inside <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` That would be no problem.''
