<HEAD>U.N. Chief Hopes For 1988 Independence Referendum In Western
Sahara</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> says he hopes an independence referendum can be held in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> this year and offered detailed proposals to end the guerrilla war there. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief urged <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and the Polisario pro-independence movement to respond to his proposals by Sept. 1. Details of the ideas were not released. <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> has occupied the territory since the Spanish colonial administration withdrew from what had been the <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> protectorate in 1975. Fighting with the Marxist-led Polisario movement began soon after. <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION> jointly ran the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> until <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION> withdrew from the conflict in 1979. <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>'s battle with <ORGANIZATION> Polisario </ORGANIZATION> has engaged most of its 100,000-man army and has cost <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> up to $ 2 million a day. Nearly 10,000 people have been killed in the war. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> presented his proposals for organizing a cease-fire and a referendum on Thursday to representatives of <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and Polisario, and to the Organization of African Unity, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION>. He said details are being kept confidential, but added that the `` rather long document'' was the result of extensive discussions among the parties, so `` they wo n't be extremely surprised'' by his suggestions. `` The current chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> OAU </ORGANIZATION> and I have carried out a number of consultations with the parties to the conflict in order to find the means to bring about practical conditions which would allow the people of the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> to freely exercise their right to self-determination through a credible referendum, and without military or administrative constraints,'' said the secretary-general. Asked if the referendum will be held this year, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> replied: `` That is our hope.'' <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> made little effort to develop the 110,000-square-mile wilderness, about the size of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. It is rich in phosphates and possibly potash and iron ore but had a population of only about 75,000 when <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> pulled out. Polisario claims to have 16,000 heavily armed guerrillas operating in the desert. Moroccan officers estimate guerrilla strength at fewer than 4,000.
