<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The world's second-largest convenience store chain says it will postpone a plan to deny medical benefits to employees with ailments related to drugs, alcohol or AIDS because of a `` general misunderstanding'' of the policy. Adopted in January by Circle K stores, the policy met with a storm of protest when it was publicly disclosed last week. The company said it would no longer pay for employees' medical care for illnesses resulting from `` personal lifestyle decisions,'' including the use of alcohol or drugs, self-inflicted injury, or infection with acquired immune deficiency syndrome through any means other than blood transfusions. The policy applied to about 3,000 Circle K employees hired since Jan. 1. The company said no employee has been denied coverage so far as a result of it. Since the company is self-insured, its health care plan is not covered by state regulations banning such restrictions. Most health insurance policies exclude coverage for suicide attempts but cover claims related to AIDS and substance abuse. The Phoenix-based company has about 26,000 employees at more than 4,000 stores in 27 states. It also has about 800 other stores in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. It had sales of about $ 2 billion last year. <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Eller </PERSON>, Circle K Corps.'s chairman and chief executive officer, announced Thursday that the plan's implementation would be delayed while it was reviewed by company officials. `` A general misunderstanding of the policy has arisen and that needs to be clarified,'' <PERSON> Eller </PERSON> said. `` We were and still are extremely concerned about containing costs of medical insurance for employees.'' <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Buck </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> gay-rights activist, met with company officials Wednesday in an attempt to negotiate a change in the policy. He called the announcement `` an excellent, excellent signal.'' Buck said he and Circle K officials agreed on four points: _ There are ambiguities in the corporation's health-benefits policy _ The intention of the policy, which is to cut the cost of health insurance, `` is legitimate and well-meaning. _ The policy is open to review and possible revision _ The company and the gay-rights activists will meet again Monday <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, a Circle K senior vice president, said the company agreed that clarification of the policy was needed but noted the agreement was to review the policy, not cancel it. `` I do n't feel we're conceding anything at this point,'' he said. Buck, who gained prominence by directing the 1987 campaign to recall then-Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, said the primary problem with the policy was that the company became the judge of its employees' lifestyles `` That creates two problems,'' Buck said. `` One is that the employee does n't know whether he is covered in any given instance. The second is that it creates an administrative nightmare for the company in deciding on a case-by-case basis what claims it will pay for.'' Buck said some gay activists favored picketing and boycotts of Circle K stores, but he counseled against it. `` I think that they -LRB- Circle K -RRB- are willing and anxious to open good-faith negotiations,'' <PERSON> Buck </PERSON> said. `` I told them that this is an emotional issue and they -LRB- the gay community -RRB- are reacting emotionally,'' he said. `` I told the other side that they must recognize the company's goal of cost-containment is legitimate, but the policy became confused, muddled and misdirected.''
