<HEAD>Lawmaker Says Waldheim Named Allied Prisoner Saboteur, Who Was
Then Executed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> says Austrian President <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, while an officer in the German army during World War II, caused the execution of a British prisoner who led an Allied escape attempt. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> member, said Thursday that <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> should be tried on war crimes charges. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> member told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> by telephone that he based his accusations on a British historian's claims that <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> signed a <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> army intelligence report labeling British army Capt <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> a saboteur. The action constituted a virtual death sentence for <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, because <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> issued a standing order to execute Allied commandos linked to sabotage, said <PERSON> Rhode </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON>. `` We're talking about murder _ cold-blooded murder of a prisoner of war, and that is a war crime,'' <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> said. `` It did n't happen in the heat of battle It was a cold-blooded criminal act.'' <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> headed <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s private office from 1973-76 when <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, elected president two years ago, served as <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> has denied any role in executing Allied prisoners when he served as an intelligence lieutenant for Gen. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Lohr </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> E </ORGANIZATION>, which committed many atrocities in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> said <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, 69, should be prosecuted. `` I would n't particularly worry about a lower-ranking person, but <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> was a former secretary-general to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> and is now head of state in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> said. In March 1986, it was revealed that <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> was a German army lieutenant in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION> from 1942 to 1945 after <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s troops took control of <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. The World Jewish <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has accused <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> of massacres of <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> and Greek civilians and partisans, as well as deportation of Greek Jews to Nazi death camps. He was also accused of involvement in a slaughter of about 70,000 people at the Yugoslav town of <LOCATION> Kozarra </LOCATION> in 1942. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> has denied these accusations. Even so, the debate over his war past has badly marred relations between <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and frayed <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s ties with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> as well. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 placed <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> on its list of aliens prohibited from entering the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The Australian-born <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> belonged to the clandestine Special Operations Executive but wore his regular army uniform while leading an escape attempt of Allied prisoners of war across <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> said. The uniform entitled the captured officer to be treated as an ordinary POW, <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> said. But he charged that <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> interrogated the prisoner and signed the report declaring him a saboteur. A firing squad executed <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> on May 15, 1944. <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> said his charges stem from conversations with <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Montague </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodhouse </PERSON>, a historian and former member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> who ran Allied operations in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> from 1943 to 1945. <PERSON> Woodhouse </PERSON>'s report on <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> is to be published later this month in Encounter magazine. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Woodhouse </PERSON> has refused to talk to the press. <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> said he has not read the report but discussed its contents with <PERSON> Woodhouse </PERSON>, 71, now a professor of Greek studies at <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>.
