Senate </ORGANIZATION> rejected, 59-36, another provision which proposed a 10 percent reduction in the number of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military dependents living overseas. In the past year, both Democrats and Republicans on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> have complained that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> allies should pay more for allied defenses. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, in particular, has been a prime target of such criticism. Voting against the spending bill were Sens. <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON>, D-N.D.; <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>, R-Ore.; <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wis </LOCATION>. Not voting were <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, D-Del.; <PERSON> Thad </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, R-Miss.; <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON>, R-Wis.; <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON>, R-S; <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON>, R-Conn.; and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Neb </LOCATION>
