 A newspaper reporter researching a story on a hang glider pilot died along with the pilot when the craft plummeted about 300 feet and crashed, authorities said. <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, a feature writer for the <ORGANIZATION> Springfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Sun </ORGANIZATION>, and pilot <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Beyer </PERSON> died Thursday at the <LOCATION> Greene </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Skydiving Center about three miles east of this southwest <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> city. Witnesses said the glider crashed nose-first. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, 33, was doing a story on <PERSON> Beyer </PERSON>, 36, and his business, High Attitude. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> had gone along for the ride, taking pictures with a camera mounted on one of the wings. A counterweight was installed on the other wing. Sgt. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Albrinck </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> said the glider's tow rope may have wrapped around one wing when the craft was banking for a turn. The tow rope is attached to a vehicle on the ground to get the craft airborne. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, a Yellow Springs resident, had been with the paper for three years. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Minnig </PERSON>, the paper's assistant city editor, said <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> always looked for offbeat stories. `` He shined at doing people stories,'' <PERSON> Minnig </PERSON> said. Sky-diving instructor <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Seibel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Skydive </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Greene </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> described <PERSON> Beyer </PERSON>, also of <LOCATION> Yellow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, as an expert hang glider pilot.
