<SECOND>PM-Anonymous Sources,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Publishes Guidelines For Use Of Anonymous Sources</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A confidential source whose identification by the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> resulted in a jury verdict against the newspaper has prompted new guidelines at the newspaper on using anonymous sources. In a front page announcement Thursday, the newspaper described the new guidelines to its readers. `` We know that some readers are concerned about recent questions involving the use of anonymous sources in the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>. So are we, and we're taking action to deal with those questions,'' <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> Executive Editor <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> wrote. The announcement follows a verdict granting damages to a public relations man who gave the paper and other news organizations information about a political opponent's shoplifting charge six days before a 1982 election. He gave the information on condition he would remain anonymous and claimed in his suit that identification of him by the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pioneer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> hurt his career. <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> also said a recent Star Tribune article on the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> that reported on `` alleged wrongdoing on the basis of anonymous sources who did n't have firsthand knowledge to support their account'' illustrated the risks to fairness and accuracy that can result from use of anonymous sources. In a third recent incident, the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> recalled all 640,000 copies of its Sunday magazine scheduled to appear one weekend because, <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> said, a person quoted by name in the magazine said she had been promised anonymity. The guidelines make three main points, <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> said: _ While anonymous sources are a critical element of some important stories, frequent reliance on them increases the risk of inaccurate or unfair journalism and can adversely affect the newspaper's credibility with readers _ Anonymous statements and quotes should be published only when necessary to provide important information and only after both a reporter and editor are satisfied that the paper is meeting its standards for accuracy and fairness _ Promises of confidentiality to sources that are not in the newspaper's or the readers' best interests should be avoided, but once made, will be honored except in the most extraordinary circumstances <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> said the guidelines `` replace the mostly unwritten guidelines and standards we've relied on before.'' On July 22, a <ORGANIZATION> Hennepin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury found that the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Pioneer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dispatch </ORGANIZATION> broke a contract by identifying <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> as a confidential source for a story and must pay him a total of $ 700,000 in damages. The newspapers are appealing the verdict. Reporters for the two newspapers, who separately accepted court documents from <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> on condition his identity not be revealed, were overruled by their editors, who decided to name <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> said that, under the new guidelines, `` a reporter should not promise anonymity in a situation similar to <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>'s, but if the reporter makes such a promise, the editors will honor it.''
</TEXT>
