<SECOND>PM-Intensive Care,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Intensive-Care Patients Would Undergo Treatment Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new study finds that most elderly patients who survived one life-threatening illness would submit to intensive care a second time, but doctors say that finding leads to serious questions about the use of resources. `` We undertook this study to help doctors deal with one dilemma _ when to use life-sustaining treatment _ and we've come up with another,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Danis </PERSON>, one of the authors of the study published in today's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The subjects of the study were 160 people, 55 or older, who were admitted to intensive care at <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> for at least 24 hours during 1983, the authors said. Of those interviewed, 74 percent later reported they would be completely willing to undergo intensive care again to prolong survival for any period, even as brief as one month, the study said. Four percent said they were unwilling to undergo more intensive care for any period. Of the remaining 22 percent, most expressed varying preferences depending on duration of survival. `` The patients in our study are saying they want to receive highly technical care under almost any condition _ as late as the last month of their life,'' Ms. <PERSON> Danis </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> said Thursday. `` And our society is going to have to think about what's the most appropriate use of our medical-care resources. It may turn out that these are wishes that will prove very difficult to fill.'' The patients' preferences appeared to hold true regardless of quality of life, life expectancy, age, severity of illness, length of stay or intensive-care cost, the study found. Families surveyed on behalf of patients who had died or been left incompetent after intensive-care treatment felt the same way, indicating the feeling did not depend on successful treatment. `` You have to recognize the limitations of the study,'' Ms. <PERSON> Danis </PERSON> said. `` The patients who provided our subjects already had shown a willingess to undergo intensive-care treatment in the face of one life-threatening illness. But that could also be one of its strengths. `` Many times, doctors face life-sustaining decisions without any input from the patients. This study informs physicians about the opinions of patients who've been in that spot.'' But one researcher questioned the finding that quality of life concerns had just a small impact on patient preference. In an editorial accompanying the study, <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zweibel </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>'s department of medicine, said the study dealt with quality-of-life considerations only in a general way. `` Evidence suggests that when faced with such decisions, patients consider a number of more concrete factors,'' such as the presence and level of long-term pain, likelihood of getting better, ability for self-care and mobility, ability to think straight and burden on family, said Ms. <PERSON> Zweibel </PERSON>, a researcher in social policy and aging.
