<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American and Soviet educators are learning new ways to teach students about each other's country by grappling with such tough issues as the death penalty in an unusual program. But the educators are also discovering how common their worries are. `` I am struck by how much we are all in the same boat,'' said <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitrofanovich </PERSON> <PERSON> Bannov </PERSON>, the principal of a secondary school in <LOCATION> Novosibirsk </LOCATION>. He is one of 40 teachers, administrators and researchers at the two-week program at <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. Among the many problems the groups share, he said, were `` the evaluation of teachers and students and staff, and the improving of education. Everybody says teachers should teach better, as if a child was a pan into which you could pour information like water.'' The program was planned by the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pedagogical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and Educators for Social Responsibility, a non-profit <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> organization with 15,000 members, founded in 1981 to help educators teach students a sense of social responsibility. The purpose of the education summit is to share insights into the ways each country teaches its children about the other and to break through the propaganda for a better understanding of the two nations. Lessons about each other's country `` are fraught with problems, strong feelings, misinformation, deeply embedded assumptions and resistance to new information, all related to tensions in U.S.-Soviet relations,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Dieringer </PERSON>, associate director of Educators for Social Responsibility. The program opened Tuesday with frank talks about how each group thought the other perceived it. The Soviets, for example, said they thought Americans saw them as aggressors `` trying to take over the world,'' <PERSON> Dieringer </PERSON> said. `` We thought that they thought there was a great disparity between the rich and poor in our country and that we do n't care about the poor,'' he said. `` In many cases there's some kernel of truth in these stereotypes, but they are so exaggerated ... that they serve to distort and limit our understanding of each other.'' Also on the agenda is an examination of each country's textbooks, a look at educational reforms in both countries and strategies for teaching controversial issues using human rights as case studies Thursday, the groups learned `` believing exercises,'' a way of suspending judgment to understand other viewpoints before looking at them critically. They were asked to make statements supporting the position that `` there are some crimes so horrible and so abusive that they demand capital punishment.'' For many participants, it was impossible to suspend their doubts about the death penalty enough to understand how others could support it. `` This issue is so loaded for me that it comes up against my strongest bias,'' said an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> woman. A Soviet woman said she could n't `` imagine this institution,'' although the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, like many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> states, has a death penalty. The idea for the gathering was laid out in a 1987 memorandum of cooperation between the Academy and <PERSON> Dieringer </PERSON>'s group, he said. The list of cooperative ventures also included working together on curriculum and exchanging articles that would be published, unedited, in each organization's respective journals. A team of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> educators visited the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for a week last year to plan the program and a Soviet team came to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in March for further planning. The next institute, on critical thinking, will be held next summer in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
