<HEAD>Resigning President Has History Of Suppressing Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Burma</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> first rose to prominence in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> by commanding an army company that shot and killed 22 protesting students in a 1962 riot at <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Last March, when thousands of students went on a rampage in some of the worst rioting in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s history, it again was <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> who led the forces that put them down. Analysts had suggested the 64-year-old hard-liner would be a logical scapegoat as the government of Ne Win, his close ally, sought to appease critics and stabilize the country. Instead, <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> emerged last month as <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s most powerful leader, succeeding <PERSON> Ne </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON>, who resigned. Protests against his authoritarian rule intensified this week, and troops shot and killed at least 95 demonstrators. Today, <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> resigned as president and as chairman of the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> _ virtually the country's sole political institution. <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> joined the army in 1942 when <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> officers, including Ne Win, were siding with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> against the Allies - specifically <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, which had colonized the onetime kingdom As the war progressed, the officers switched allegiance to the Allies, realizing <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> posed as much a threat to <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> independence as had the British. Independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in 1948 was followed by a chaotic, 14-year experiment with democracy. That experiment ended in 1962, the year Ne Win seized power in a military coup and began to enforce his brand of economic socialism, military-backed authoritarian rule and isolation from much of the world. That same year, <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> led his army unit in quelling the protest at <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, firmly establishing his reputation as an unbending leader prepared to wield an iron fist to root out opposition. Little has been pubished about <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> and others in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s senior hierarchy, most of whom live secluded lives away from the public eye <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> retired from the army and in 1977 became a member of the party's guiding body, the Central Executive Committee. He took the No. 4 party slot of joint general secretary in 1985. Also in 1985, he was named secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, the No. 3 position in the government after president and vice president. The 28-member council directs all state organs. He has also held ministerial portfolios for cooperatives, transport, communications, and home affairs. On March 18, in a day that was later dubbed `` Bloody Friday,'' thousands of students stormed through downtown <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>, burning cars and shouting anti- government slogans for the second time in three months. The `` Lon Htein,'' or riot police, were called out, reinforced by regular army units and armored vehicles. According to Western diplomatic and <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> sources, <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> commanded the police from a tactical command headquarters at the government broadcast station. <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> overruled some leaders who wanted to handle the riot more leniently, the sources said. The government has since admitted to 43 deaths but more than 100 people are believed to have been killed. Analysts, among them the respected <ORGANIZATION> Hong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Far </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION>, had suggested <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> would take the fall for the violence, which deepened anti-government sentiments. Instead, after he became president, troops under his command again fired on demonstrators.
