it does not require the seemingly endless development of new and more expensive nuclear weapons systems, particularly when, thanks to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Secretary <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, we may have the best opportunity in our lifetime to build a safer world.'' Because of that progress, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said, a greater share of the defense budget should be spent to improve conventional forces. `` We need strong, well-equipped, well-trained conventional forces,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said after the tour of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dix </LOCATION>, where he met with two men with whom he went through basic training. He also said the military should be prepared to help with anti-terrorism and anti-drug operations. `` We have to build strong military forces in this country based on sound planning and tough management, not wishful thinking and blank checks,'' he said, criticizing expensive weapons systems favored by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and the current <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> procurement scandal. While in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> attended two fund-raisers which raised well in excess of $ 500,000 for the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s 1988 `` Victory Fund.'' After a reception at the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> governor's mansion today, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was headed to <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, where aides said he would emphasize his commitment to anti-drug efforts and criticize the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for cutting <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> funding and other moves <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> contends have undermined the war on drugs.
