<HEAD>Officials Urge Reform Of Doctors' Training To Keep People Well</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with declaration issued. Pickup
6th graf pvs, ``He said...'' DELETES last graf pvs to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 World health officials today approved a strategy to promote better world health care by training doctors to emphasize disease prevention and to pass this knowledge along to their patients. `` We want doctors everywhere to concentrate on how to keep people well, rather than always be thinking of new ways to cure them when they fall ill,'' said Dr. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> of <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, a former head of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> issued its declaration at the close of the five-day conference today. The document sets out principles to change and improve world health. `` Thousands suffer and die every day from diseases which are preventable, curable or self-inflicted and millions have no ready access to health care of any kind,'' said the declaration, which was approved by 160 experts invited to the conference. `` The aim of medical education is to produce doctors who will promote the health of all people _ not merely deliver curative services to those who can afford it, or for those for whom it is readily available,'' the declaration said. It set out steps for the radical reform of medical education through cooperation with education and health ministries and community health services. Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Children's Fund, said it was now possible to improve dramatically the health of the next generation. But he said parents were not being instructed on how to protect their children at small cost from the `` great scourges'' of disease including diarrhea, measles, tetanus, whooping cough and acute respiratory infection. He said these diseases account for more than two-thirds of the 14 million child deaths in the world each year. <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said ways must be found to give people the knowledge to improve their own health. Dr. <PERSON> Hiroshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakajima </PERSON>, newly appointed director-general of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters that some countries had too many doctors trained in curative medicine when the real need was for disease prevention. The conference was told that Scots were turning to alternative medicine and setting up self-help groups because of dissatisfaction with doctors. `` They are doing this because they feel they are not getting enough time or consideration or applied concern from their doctors,'' said <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Headland </PERSON>, secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Scottish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Councils </ORGANIZATION>, a liaison body of regional health authorities. Mrs. <PERSON> Headland </PERSON> said women's self-help groups were set up in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> to try to reduce dependence on tranquilizers, a problem they blamed in part on doctors who prescribed the drugs over long periods. `` People want more information about their treatment and they want to be involved more in the decisions taken. They want to be treated with a bit of dignity and respect,'' she said. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Walton </PERSON>, a psychiatrist, educator and president of the Edinburgh-based <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> which organized the conference, said in an interview that too often, doctors do not listen to their patients nor consider how to keep them fit. `` They only think about them when they are ill. Medical education must extend to take care of people in the community _ in their homes and at work,'' <PERSON> Walton </PERSON> said He said there is a serious problem in some countries of too many doctors. `` <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, for example, has 1,500 unemployed doctors and a union for unemployed doctors. They are taxi drivers, waiters ... <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> ca n't find the salaries to pay doctors whom they could well use,'' <PERSON> Walton </PERSON> said.
