<HEAD>Hospital Withdraws Plans For Hinckley Field Trip</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: TOP 12 grafs new with comments from prosecutor, more complete
quote from letter; picks up 8th graf, Brady remains; St.
Elizabeths, no apostrophe, is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mental hospital holding <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> today dropped its proposal to take the man who shot President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on a field trip, as prosecutors turned up new writings by the presidential assailant. Dr. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elizabeths </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>'s forensic services unit, told a federal judge that the decision to drop the request was based on material received by the hospital Thursday night Reading a letter to U.S. District Judge <PERSON> Barrington </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> said, `` The <ORGANIZATION> Forensic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has determined that further clinical assessment by Mr. <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON>'s treatment staff is necessary before it would permit him to participate'' in a day-long field trip Comments by attorneys on both sides during the brief hearing indicated the material turned up by the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> consisted of letters by <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> to an unidentified third party. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> to unseal the material, which he said the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> had obtained through an investigation. Defense lawyer <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> described the material as letters written by <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON>. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> refused to unseal the writings, which were turned over to the court Thursday, until <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> could respond to the government's request they be made public The defense lawyer was given until Tuesday to file a written objection. Outside the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Courthouse, <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> told reporters the writings should be made public because `` they relate to a matter of great national importance, they relate to an individual who shot the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' `` The public should be aware of what these materials are,'' <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> indicated that the material turned up by the <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> were not known to <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeths </LOCATION> officials until Thursday night and was the basis for the hospital's decision to withdraw its request. `` We provided materials to <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeths </LOCATION> last night; they withdrew their request for an off-site visit this morning,'' <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said. The hospital decision was announced a day after federal prosecutors cited `` disturbing entries'' made this week in <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON>'s psychiatric treatment record. <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> has been held at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeths </LOCATION> since he was acquitted by reason of insanity of charges he shot and wounded <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, presidential press secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, and two other men on March 30, 1981. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> remains confined to a wheelchair as a result of crippling injuries suffered during the shooting. The hospital had not formally made known its plans, but officials at the facility had indicated they want to take <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> on a supervised outing such as a picnic or a bowling party, according to court records. <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said in Thursday's pleading that the latest treatment entries support the government's demand to review letters and writings seized from <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON>'s room in April 1987. The writings include correspondence with multiple murderer <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Bundy </PERSON>, who is held on <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s death row. Hospital officials abruptly dropped their request to allow <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> to visit his family over the Easter holiday last year after the Bundy correspondence was disclosed. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, who presided at <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON>'s trial for the attempted assassination of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, ordered <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeths </LOCATION> to let prosecutors examine the treatment records that figured in its decision to propose the field trip. But <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> has yet to rule on the government's request to see those writings, which he placed under court seal last summer. In a pleading filed earlier this week, <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON>'s lawyers opposed allowing the government to see the sealed material. `` As an insanity acquittee, Mr. <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> is receiving treatment from the hospital with the ultimate goal of being rehabilitated,'' the lawyers said. `` For this treatment to succeed, Mr. <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> needs to have some sense of privacy. The government wishes to invade that privacy without any legitimate need to do so.''
