<HEAD>CIA Won't Recruit at University of Colorado This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, apparently weary of the controversy and protests surrounding its recruiting at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION>, has decided to move off campus this year. In 1986 and earlier, <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> recruiting on the <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION> campus resulted in demonstrations and arrests. Some students uninterested in <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> work waded through the pickets anyway to talk to recruiters as a sort of counterprotest, university placement director <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said Thursday. Many with sincere interest stayed away. For recruitment purposes, the entire process was inefficient, he said. This year, the agency will accept individual applications and interview potential employees elsewhere, <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said. `` The process avoids big one-time, one-place confrontations,'' <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said.
