<HEAD>Outlawed Tribal Group Agrees To End 10-year Insurgency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An outlawed tribal group today agreed to end its 10-year-old campaign for an independent homeland in the northeastern state of <LOCATION> Tripura </LOCATION>, a government official announced. The <ORGANIZATION> Tribal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Volunteers </ORGANIZATION> signed a memorandum of understanding with federal and state governments, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s interior minister, <PERSON> Buta </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, said in Parliament. Under the agreement, worked out in three months of negotiations, the insurgents agreed to surrender their weapons within a month and abide by the Constitution. In return, the tribal group will be given 20 seats in the new state legislature. The chief minister of <LOCATION> Tripura </LOCATION>, <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Majumder </PERSON>, said the accord would bring peace and stability to the state, bordering <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>. Authorities estimate nearly 600 died during the insurgency. The problem started in 1951 with a steady influx of settlers from <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. The economic and social patterns in the state shifted when the tribe members who originally settled the area were outnumbered. In the 1970s, tribal unrest gave rise to the <ORGANIZATION> Tribal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Volunteers </ORGANIZATION>, which declared `` Independent Tripura'' as its objective and took up arms. The violence escalated, and in June 1980, nearly 400 people, mostly non-tribals, were massacred. The group set up its underground headquarters in the <LOCATION> Chittagong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tracts </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> and started training volunteers. In April 1983, the leader of the underground movement, <PERSON> Bijay </PERSON> <PERSON> Hrangkhawl </PERSON>, rejected suggestions by then-Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> for a negotiated settlement between the organization and the state government. In 1984, the organization was outlawed. But the violence continued. In January, 97 people were killed. Non-tribals threatened retaliation, and the <ORGANIZATION> Tribal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Volunteers </ORGANIZATION> vowed to disrupt scheduled state elections, prompting the federal government to deploy the army. The elections were held a month later despite the threats, and Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> wrested control of the state from the <ORGANIZATION> Marxist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. In May, the <ORGANIZATION> Tribal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Volunteers </ORGANIZATION> said they were willing to negotiate a settlement.
