<HEAD>Seven Bus Passengers Killed in Bomb Blast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A time bomb planted by suspected Sikh radicals exploded today on the roof of a state-owned bus, police said, and at least seven people were killed and 35 injured. The bomb exploded late this afternoon, 20 minutes after the vehicle left the crowded bus terminal at <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION> for the town of <LOCATION> Shazadpur </LOCATION> in neighboring <LOCATION> Haryana </LOCATION> state, police chief Surinder <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Brar </PERSON> said. Almost at the same time, police detected and defused another time bomb planted in <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION>'s most popular shopping center, <PERSON> Brar </PERSON> said. Both bombs are suspected to have been planted by Sikh militants, he added. <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION> is the joint capital of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Haryana </LOCATION> states. A separatist campaign by Sikh insurgents in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> has killed 1,680 people this year. `` It was an encounter with death,'' said <PERSON> Yash </PERSON> <PERSON> Bir </PERSON>, a passenger on the bus who suffered burn injuries in the explosion. `` I was unconscious. I do not know who brought me to hospital.'' <PERSON> Bir </PERSON> spoke to reporters from a bed in a <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION> hospital, where most of the injured were taken. Doctors said five were in serious condition. The victims were not immediately identified. <PERSON> Brar </PERSON> said the bomb was planted on the bus' rooftop luggage carrier. About 70 passengers were in the vehicle when the bomb exploded, he said. In other parts of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, Sikh militants were blamed for five other killings that occurred Thursday night and today, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said. At least three victims were Sikhs, the news agency said. The militants have targetted members of the Hindu community and moderate Sikhs in their campaign. Sikhs form only 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people but form a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Radicals have been agitating for an independent Sikh homeland since 1982, claiming discrimination by <PERSON> Hindus </PERSON>, who form 80 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
