<HEAD>Mutiny Aboard Dutch Vessel Ends Peacefully</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with mutiny ending, details. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DEN HELDER, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 120-member crew of an offshore vessel surrendered command of the ship after taking it over early today in a labor dispute, a spokesman for the <LOCATION> Dutch </LOCATION> seamen's union said. J.G. <PERSON> Harmsen </PERSON> said the incident, in which the Spanish crew of the Dutch-owned <PERSON> Hermod </PERSON> seized command from Dutch officers for three hours, ended peacefully after a misunderstanding about the weeklong dispute was cleared up. Earlier today, the captain of the Hermod, which hauls heavy rig equipment for the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> offshore oil industry, issued a distress call requesting navy assistance because of the mutiny, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. `` Apparently there were some violent threats towards the commanding officers,'' the spokesman, Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Willem </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Geneste </PERSON> said. It was unclear whether the Dutch officers had been locked up during the incident. <PERSON> Harmsen </PERSON> said the crew was on strike for a week when it seized power today. He said that early in the day, the captain asked the crew to suspend its strike and weigh anchor in light of worsening weather conditions in the area where the vessel was operating, 100 miles northwest of this Dutch navy port. `` The crew failed to understand that the captain asked this because of safety reasons,'' <PERSON> Harmsen </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>. `` They thought it was another company ploy.'' <PERSON> Harmsen </PERSON> said the leaders of the mutiny abandoned their action after he explained the purpose of the captain's request by ship-to-shore radio. `` The whole incident was based on a misunderstanding,'' <PERSON> Harmsen </PERSON> said, adding that the strike had not been called off. The Hermod is owned by the Dutch offshore construction company <ORGANIZATION> Heerema </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION>. Company spokeswoman <PERSON> Ria </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kok </PERSON> refused to comment on the incident but said the request for navy assistance had been withdrawn. The labor dispute on board the <PERSON> Hermod </PERSON> and several other vessels involves <ORGANIZATION> Heerema </ORGANIZATION>'s lay-off procedures. The majority of the company's 950 Spanish sailors have short-term labor contracts and are not protected by Dutch labor law. The sailors are demanding better conditions in dismissal cases, according to <PERSON> Harmsen </PERSON>.
