<HEAD>Boston Youth Corps Seeks To Serve as National Model</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leaders are <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> graduates who could be earning more than $ 100,000 a year. The participants are high school and college students who could be at the beach. Instead, they're working as a sort of urban Peace Corps that organizers hope will set a national example The program, called City Year, is a privately funded community service project. Fifty students ages 18 to 21, from high school dropouts to <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> students, were culled from 150 applicants. They begin their days at 8 a.m. sharp on <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> Common with 20 minutes of calisthenics. If they're late, they do extra exercises. They spend the rest of the day on various projects, battling the summer's searing heat and humidity as well as urban blight. One day they sort surplus food in a warehouse, other days they help paint and renovate shelters for the homeless, clear brush from vacant lots or work with disabled children. `` We call it City Year, because we thought of it as being like junior year, senior year, then City Year,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, 27, a recent <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> graduate who is one of the group's directors `` We say, ` Why not spend a city year helping your city before going on to college?''' City Year ends this summer but organizers hope to get enough funding to make the program year-round. They plan to start it up again next year. <PERSON> Raquel </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON>, 17, said she's `` learned a lot about other people.'' She said she enjoyed working on a project with disabled children so much that she found it `` painful to leave.'' Though youth corps exist in other cities, City Year President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Khazei </PERSON> said most of them are government-funded. <PERSON> Khazei </PERSON> began working on the program during his last year at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> with two other students and a fourth person from another college. They took their idea around to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s business community in the hope of receiving funding and were rewarded. <ORGANIZATION> Bain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Equitable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and General Cinema each donated $ 25,000 to fund four of the five 10-person City Year teams. Citizen contributions funded the fifth team. `` One of the big issues with national service is how do you fund it?'' said <PERSON> Khazei </PERSON>. `` Well, we've reached out to the private sector to show it can be done.'' <PERSON> Khazei </PERSON> said he and his colleagues prefer working to `` promote the idea of national service'' rather than taking high-paying corporate jobs. `` This is a lot more fun,'' he said. `` We love what we're doing. I ca n't think of anything more rewarding than working with wonderful young people.'' <PERSON> Kristen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollister </PERSON>, 27, a Brown graduate, is one of the individual team leaders. Because she knows sign language, the two hearing-impaired participants were assigned to her team. `` When I read the -LRB- program -RRB- proposal, I said, ` This is it, this is what I have to do to make a difference,''' she said. <PERSON> Hollister </PERSON> said the highlight of her team's work came on a recent sweltering day at a shelter for the homeless. The students spent the day on the third floor of the shelter reupholstering chairs for the women in the shelter. `` Each of them got to carry a chair down to the women at the end of the day,'' said <PERSON> Hollister </PERSON>. `` When the women saw the chairs, they all cheered. It was such a high.'' A stint spent working at the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> for disabled children was the high point for many of the students. <PERSON> Winda </PERSON> <PERSON> Maldonado </PERSON>, 17, who is deaf, said it was a revelation to her to care for children with greater disabilities than herself. `` It was my favorite place,'' she said. `` I loved it. I di n't want to leave I made so many friends.'' <PERSON> Caleb </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobson-Sive </PERSON>, 17, a prep school student, said that prior to City Year, he `` might have avoided people like the ones there. But I look at handicapped people totally differently now. This -LRB- City Year -RRB- has changed my outlook on a lot of things.''
