<HEAD>Party Town Awaits Biggest Republican Party of the Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bourbon Street has always appealed to the prurient, but French Quarter merchants have draped <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>' famous party street with red, white and blue to attract the patriotic as well during the Republican National Convention <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags hang next to drawings of bare breasted women beckoning to passers-by while multicolored bunting competes for attention with a fake pair of women's legs that swing forward and back from two stories above. On this naughty street of take-out drinks and knockout strip shows, merchants are hoping to lure Republicans with traditional tawdriness and newfound politics. `` He's tan, rested and ready _ <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> in 1988'' adorns one T-shirt bearing a black and white likeness of the former president. Other shirts found in various souvenir shops carry the standard logo of the official 1988 GOP convention. Bourbon Street is ready for the Republicans. The question, however, is are the Republicans ready for Bourbon Street? `` Everybody should see this city,'' said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON>, a delegate from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` There are lots of weirdos here, but everyone should see them. It's hot, but excellent.'' Wrought-iron balconies, bars named for pirates, provocative dancers of both sexes and 24-hour liquor attract an eclectic group. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Montolbano </PERSON>, the doorman at <ORGANIZATION> Pat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> O'Briens </ORGANIZATION> where tourists slurp rosy-colored Hurricanes in a glass they can take home, said some Republicans have already experienced the street. `` You can spot ` em by the way they dress in those $ 800 suits and the way they carry themselves. Power tie, power look, the whole bit,'' he said. Dancer <PERSON> Bonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Holloway </PERSON> said she expects the Republicans to party just like everyone else. `` If they get drunk, they should spend money. There's going to be a lot of men at this convention, they said, so it'll be good for us,'' she said. The doorman at Papa <PERSON> Joe </PERSON>'s, which bills itself as having the only female impersonators on Bourbon Street, said Republicans seem to enjoy looking at men dressed up like women. `` They seem to be having fun. At least they get a couple of laughs out of here,'' said <PERSON> Manny </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreland </PERSON>. But a hostess at the Coffee Pot, around the corner from <LOCATION> Bourbon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, and a bartender at Court Liquors To Go said they've noticed little change _ yet. The French Quarter, of course, is not the only place <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> likes to party. `` A Grand Party for the Grand Old Party'' started the convention festivities on Friday with a picnic in <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. Probably the only family event scheduled for the week, the Grand Party featured bands, choirs, fireworks and free rides on the park's narrow-gauge trains and flying horses, a turn-of-the-century carousel. The Elephant Romp on Saturday will attract delegates and people willing to shell out $ 100 per person for a trip to the Audubon Zoo. The <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> hopes to raise $ 400,000 to help defray city costs for hosting the convention. Tents featuring <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> themes, food and music will be spread about the zoological park. Beginning Sunday, fancy clothes and political bigwigs will dominate the many private parties on social calendars. Among those featured convention week are a masked ball for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> insiders at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION