<FIRST>u i AM-Burma-SeinLwin     08-12 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma-Sein Lwin,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sein Lwin Made Name by Killing Rebel Leader, Suppressing Riots</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Burma, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> rose to prominence by personally killing a Burmese rebel leader in 1950 and commanding an army company that shot down rioting <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> students in 1962. When thousands of students went on a rampage last March in some of the worst riots <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> has experienced, <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> led the forces that stopped them. Analysts had suggested the 64-year-old former general would be a logical scapegoat as the government of Ne Win, his close ally, sought to appease critics and stabilize the country. Instead, <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> emerged last month as <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s most powerful leader to succeed Ne Win, who resigned after wielding near absolute power since a coup 26 years ago. Protests of authoritarian rule intensified this week and soldiers killed at least 95 demonstrators. Protesters carried placards calling <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> a `` dog, Nazi and butcher of students,'' and many Burmese said he was the most hated man in the country. On Friday, <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> resigned as president of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> and chairman of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Little has been published about <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> and others in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s senior hierarchy, most of whom live in seclusion According to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Badgley </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> expert at <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> is a Mon tribesman born in <LOCATION> Mattama </LOCATION> village. The <LOCATION> Mons </LOCATION> are one of several ethnic minorities in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> country. He completed the fourth grade at most in a <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monastery school. Many Burmese still look down on him for his low level of education and relative lack of manners. <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> joined the army in 1942 when <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> officers, including Ne Win, were siding with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> against the Allies _ specifically <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, colonial master of the former kingdom. As the war progressed, the officers switched allegiance, realizing <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was as much a threat to <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s independence as <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Independence in 1948 was followed by a chaotic, 14-year experiment with democracy. Maj. <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> became known during that period as the man who cornered and killed <PERSON> Sabaw </PERSON> <PERSON> U </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON>, leader of the ethnic <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> rebellion. He developed a reputation as a man with courage and decisiveness, but limited vision and a strain of brutality. Among the troops, his nickname was `` chinthe,'' for the mythical lion that guards the entrances of <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> temples in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>. He once was Ne Win's personal aide, and was at the leader's side when Ne Win seized power in 1962 and began enforcing his brand of economic socialism, military-backed authoritarian rule and isolation from much of the world. Soon after the coup, <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> led his army unit in quelling the riots at <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, firmly establishing his reputation as an unbending leader prepared to wield an iron fist to root out opposition. Most Burmese are interested in the supernatural, but <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> has a preoccupation with astrology, magic and black arts and for three years was the secret publisher of a magazine called Veda dealing with such matters, <ORGANIZATION> Badgley </ORGANIZATION> said in an interview. <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> retired from the army and in 1977 joined the party's Central Executive Committee He won the No. 4 party post of joint general secretary in 1985 and also became secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, the No. 3 position in the government after president and vice president. He has held ministerial portfolios for cooperatives, transport, communications, and home affairs. On March 18, a day later dubbed `` Bloody Friday,'' thousands of students swept through downtown <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>, burning cars and shouting anti-government slogans. It was the second student outburst in three months. The `` Lon Htein,'' or riot police, were called out, reinforced by regular army units and armored vehicles. Western diplomats and <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> sources said <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> commanded the police from a tactical headquarters at the government broadcast station. They said he overruled some leaders who wanted to be more lenient. The government has acknowledged 43 deaths, but more than 100 people are believed to have been killed.
