<SECOND>PM-US Smuggling, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0590,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three US Officials Caught Taking Material Out of Soviet Union</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lead to clarify that Fitzwater did not specify that the
Energy Department was the agency involved; INSERTS 8th graf, The
team, to show that individuals involved were geologists.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three members of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government team taking part in a nuclear testing experiment in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> engaged in `` some unauthorized souvenir collection'' there, the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> said today. Presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, however, said that based on information available so far to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, `` we do n't believe it was intelligence activity of any kind. `` The individuals picked up and attempted to ship on for their personal use some rock samples, a piece of barbed wire, an <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> wrench and a hammer,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> told reporters at the White House. `` The individuals involved have been removed from the list of those who might return for the experiment,'' he said. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> noted that the team was in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> under the auspices of an agreement, announced by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, for a joint verification experiment in the field of nuclear testing. `` We do n't believe it was intelligence activity of any kind, but it was a personal mistake on their part,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, adding that `` we have informed the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> of this, yes.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> declined to divulge the names of the three people involved. The team apparently was under the auspices of the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said only that it included geologists who were there to work with rocks and minerals related to the experiment. The materials were discovered by Soviets inspecting equipment crates being prepared for shipment back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said Deputy Press Secretary <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> Popadiuk </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported in today's editions that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> had issued a formal diplomatic protest over the July 17 incident. But <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said there had been no formal exchanges. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official told the newspaper that both the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> were trying to resolve the problem in a `` low-key'' manner. The team was in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> under an agreement by which the superpowers are allowing each other to observe and monitor each other's nuclear blasts. The agreement is not connected to the monitoring of weapons under the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty, a <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said. `` There's no question but that we stepped over the bounds of the agreement,'' the newspaper quoted an unidentified senior administration official as saying Thursday. The official said the incident presumably stemmed from an innocent mistake. The attempted shipment by the Americans, who were not identified, involved materials such as tools and wire associated with Soviet nuclear test preparations at the test site near <LOCATION> Semipalatinsk </LOCATION> in south-central <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> as well as soil and rock samples of potential use in assessing yields of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear blasts, the newspaper quoted officials as saying. The items were found by Soviet authorities during a search of a crate of personal belongings of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official and two employees of private firms under contract to the federal government, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said. Spokesmen for the departments of energy and state as well as the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> declined to comment. The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, has conducted a secret investigation of the incident. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barker </PERSON>, assistant secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> for atomic energy and chairman of the military liaison to the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> the Americans were `` absolutely not'' deliberately trying to collect prohibited materials. When contacted late Thursday by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Barker </PERSON> denied making the comment to the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> and refused to speak about the issue. The Soviet Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a private protest July 25 to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomats that demanded permanent expulsion of the three and a detailed explanation, the newspaper reported. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official and one of the contractor employees had left the country before the protest was issued, and the other contractor employee was allowed to remain in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> denied he was responsible, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official not identified by the newspaper said, `` We are trying to resolve it in a low-key way ... and the Soviets are, too.'' The special nuclear experiment for which the team was in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is scheduled for next month at the test site near <LOCATION> Semipalatinsk </LOCATION>. The Post quoted unidentified senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials as saying the incident was not expected to halt the progress of the agreement, which also calls for observation of tests at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> site in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>. The project in question was part of the Joint Verification Experiment concerning nuclear testing and `` has nothing to do with on-site inspection or the INF Treaty,'' <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Cmdr. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Pease </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday night.
