<HEAD>New Software Allows Composers To Write More Music, Faster</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Ran in 7th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Programmers hope a new software program that can print out music as it's played will score a hit with composers. `` You play, it prints. It's a speeding up of the whole process,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Borowicz </PERSON>, a co-creator of the program. `` It understands everything about standard music notation and it can accurately transcribe what you play.'' The program, called `` Finale'' by Coda Music Software of <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, was unveiled Thursday at the <ORGANIZATION> Macworld </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Expo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION>'88. The program can translate information from a keyboard, guitar or wind instrument. <PERSON> Borowicz </PERSON>, a composer and computer scientist, said he and his partner <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrand </PERSON> worked on musical transcription software for about five years before producing the program. The software, he said, costs $ 1,000 and is `` aimed at the professional level, or the intense amateurs.'' Although he said the new program will allow composers to produce more music in less time, some musicians were hesitant to applaud the new development. <PERSON> Ran </PERSON> <PERSON> Blake </PERSON>, the director of the New England Conservatory of Music's department of Third Stream Studies, said he was personally interested but questioned whether it was an appropriate tool for students. `` I wonder if they should n't have a mentor'' to teach them such intricacies as harmony, he said. Although word processing has advanced rapidly, music notation has benefited little from technology. Some software programs allow composers to print music by punching in notes on a computer staff, but the new program frees musicians from working separately on composing, performing and editing. The new program, <PERSON> Borowicz </PERSON> said, is `` works the way the musician works. The musician does not have to work the way the software works.'' Finale allows the musician to edit a piece at any point. `` You can play it back. You can stop it at any point. You can manipulate down to the micro level,'' <PERSON> Borowicz </PERSON> said. `` You can also point to the note, drag it to where you want it, or change it.''
