<SECOND>AM-Southern Forests,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Sees Economic Problems if Softwood Depletion Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Much of the South could suffer economically if the depletion of softwood timber continues at the current pace without being replaced, a senior <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said Friday. <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> Chief F. <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> said a new study by the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> agency, state forestry agencies and universities, and the forest industry found that the annual removal of timber is greater than growth in many areas of the South. Timber is the region's leading agricultural crop, and the processing of timber and timber products is the primary source of employment, he said. `` Although the results of this study are of concern, we have also found numerous opportunities for ensuring that timber production can continue to prosper and grow in the South,'' <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> said. `` Since the 1880s, when the South's first forest was devastated by fire and poor management, two new forests have been regenerated and harvested,'' he said. `` The South's fourth forest, the forest of the future, can be even more productive.'' According to the report, 22 million acres of cropland and pasture in the South would be of more value if the lands were planted in pine trees. Conversion to timber production could increase annual softwood growth by 2.1 billion cubic feet, the report said. And the replanting of cutover and non-productive trees on cutover lands could increase net annual growth by an additional 3.2 billion cubic feet. In other words, the study showed that conversion of cropland and replanting could nearly double the South's current annual softwood growth of 5.7 billion cubic feet. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> said the report presents a challenge and an opportunity for southern farmers and landowners. `` Already, the owners of 1.5 million acres of highly erodible cropland in the South have decided to plant trees on that acreage under <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s Conservation Reserve Program, he said. `` More opportunities exist to increase timber growth profitably.'' Copies of a summary of the report, `` The <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>'s Fourth Forest: Opportunities to Increase the Resource Wealth of the South,'' are available from: <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Experiment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION>, 701 <LOCATION> Loyola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ave. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. 70113.
