<FIRST>r w AM-BusinessInventories     08-12 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Inventories,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Business Inventories Up for 18th Straight Month</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Business inventories climbed for the 18th consecutive month in June, the government said Friday, prompting some economists to warn that companies may be stockpiling goods in anticipation of higher prices. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said inventories jumped 0.7 percent to a seasonally adjusted $ 733.9 billion in June, following an identical 0.7 percent rise in May. Inventory levels have not fallen since December 1986. `` My guess is that there is a little buying ahead on inventories in anticipation of higher inflation going on. When it happens, that just adds to inflationary pressures,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said wholesale prices rose 0.5 percent in July, a 5.7 percent annual rate that was more than double the 2.2 percent rate for all of 1987. However, other economists, noting that business sales have increased more strongly than inventories, were n't troubled by the gain in goods held on shelves and backlots. Business sales surged 1.5 percent in June to $ 490.6 billion following a 0.8 percent gain in May. It was the fifth month without a decline. `` Even though inventories were up sharply, they were still in line with sales,'' said <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` It's a reflection of the export-driven turnaround in manufacturing. If you're selling more domestically and overseas, then you need more inventory,'' she said. `` There's been some hedge buying against price increases, but we think it's been fairly small,'' said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Chimerine </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, consulting firm. Inventories in June were 7.8 percent higher than a year ago, while sales were 8.1 percent higher. The June inventory accumulation was boosted by a 1.0 percent climb at the retail level, where sales were weakest, a 0.8 percent increase at the wholesale level and a 0.4 percent gain at factories. The strength in business sales was paced by a 2.5 percent jump at wholesalers. Sales from manufacturing plants climbed 1.5 percent and retail sales were up only 0.4 percent. An advance estimate of retail sales for July, released Thursday, showed a 0.5 percent increase. The combination of strongly rising sales and moderately rising inventories pushed the inventory-to-sales ratio down slightly from 1.51 in May to 1.50 in June. That means it would take 1.50 months to exhaust inventories at the June sales pace, a ratio not considered abnormally high.
