<HEAD>Citizens Get Soviets To Turn Down Noise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hungarians angry about the noise caused by low-flying Soviet military jets have succeeded in persuading the Soviets to reduce the number of training flights and to fly at a higher altitude, it was reported this week. A rare `` village meeting'' took place between residents of the small towns of <LOCATION> Szigethalom </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Szazhalombatta </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and commanders at the nearby Soviet base of <LOCATION> Toekoel </LOCATION> early this week. State television said the Hungarians pointed out cracks in walls they said were caused by the piercing noise of low-flying jets. The Soviets agreed to stop any training flights on state and religious holidays, Saturdays and Sundays, and between 2 p.m. and 4 p.m. on weekdays, television and radio reported. The number of training flights overall will be reduced and the jets will fly at a higher altitude, the media said.
