<TEXT>
 About 400 uniformed workers from the state-run railway marched through the streets Friday to demand higher wages and overtime pay. The workers from <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> Railway Administration handed a petition to <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials. A spokesman for the workers, <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ching-chang </PERSON>, said the railway company should raise their salaries and immediately make overtime payments owed to the workers. The workers did not say how much more they want. After a one-day strike by conductors in May that halted rail service throughout the island, the railway had promised to make the overtime payments over a four-year period. Railway workers earn an average of about $ 700 a month. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> legalized strikes in June but banned strikes without the authorization of labor associations.
