<HEAD>Walesa Marks Anniversary of Strikes That Launched Solidarity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> on Friday laid a wreath at a monument to fallen shipyard workers in a ceremony marking the eighth anniversary of strikes that launched the now-outlawed independent trade union. A Solidarity spokeswoman said about 2,000 shipyard workers and other Solidarity supporters attended the ceremony near the entrance to the Lenin shipyard. The crowd chanted Solidarity slogans, waved banners and sang the national anthem, said <PERSON> Joanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Wojciechowiz </PERSON>. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, wearing a Solidarity T-shirt, helped put wreaths and flowers on the monument, erected to honor striking shipyard workers killed by security forces during labor unrest in 1970. The ceremony was held two days before the official 1980 strike anniversary, which falls on a Sunday this year, to allow more workers to attend, said the Solidarity spokeswoman. On Aug. 14, 1980, workers in the Lenin shipyards in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> began a strike over reinstating a fired crane operator. Two days later the demands grew to include an independent trade union, and Solidarity was born. The union at its peak claimed about 10 million members, or nearly one-third of the nation's population. The union was crushed when martial law was imposed in 1981. It was banned by parliament the next year. Police watched the ceremony but did not intervene, witnesses said.
