<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> traded compliments with <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in a campaign pep talk Friday to top administration officials, and predicted Americans wo n't `` gamble their future on a blind date'' in the November election. `` We're going to hold the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION> with <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> declared to about 250 Cabinet and other top administration officials in a spirited pre-convention sendoff for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> next door to the White House. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, noting that many of the officials would be on the campaign trail on his behalf as surrogate speakers this fall, said they must persuade voters that `` not just one election but ... a way of life'' is at stake. `` I need you to march to victory again in November,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told the group of officials he called the `` field commanders of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> revolution.'' He told them a victory by his Democratic rival, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, would `` totally reverse'' the `` successes of this administration.'' It was <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s last scheduled campaign event before he goes to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> next Tuesday. He will appear again with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> at an airport rally there before he is formally installed as his party's presidential nominee at the Republican National Convention In the meantime, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will continue working on his acceptance speech and make his final decision on a running mate _ although he has repeatedly said he'll try to keep his choice secret until the convention is well under way. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who spoke after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, told his audience: `` Some people may cast their vote this year to thank us for the last eight years. But I suspect most people will vote for <PERSON>