<HEAD>Hunters Roust Grouse On Glorious Twelfth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Write</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hunters flocked to the heather-covered moors of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> on Friday, `` The Glorious Twelfth of August'' and the start of the grouse-hunting season popular with landed gentry and wealthy tourists. But the hunters' gunfire was muted by declining stocks of the wild red grouse, due to a parasite and vigorous protesters who drove the birds away with a pre-dawn swoop on three grouse moors. The <ORGANIZATION> Hunt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Saboteurs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which opposes blood sports, said about 300 members beat the hunters to the bushes and rousted the grouse at <LOCATION> Stanhope </LOCATION> and Gunnerside Moors in northern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and in an area near <LOCATION> Muirshell </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Country </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponton </PERSON>, a spokesman for the protesters, said they would remain on the moors all day. He described their early success as the `` most glorious day'' in efforts to ban grouse-killing. `` It has become a ` Glorious Twelfth,''' he said. `` We've saved birds lives and that's glorious.'' <PERSON> Dukes </PERSON> and lords traditionally lead hunting parties on `` The Glorious Twelfth of August'' _ not to be confused with `` The Glorious Twelfth of July,'' when Protestants in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> celebrate their victory over Roman Catholics in the Battle of the <LOCATION> Boyne </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> restaurants, which used to hire helicopters, race-car drivers and airplanes in an informal competition to whisk the first grouse from the north to their tables, have toned down the publicity stunts, partly because of the protests. `` I think over the last few years there has been very bad press,'' said a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s fashionable <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lane </LOCATION>, which ordered 10 grouse to serve Friday night. `` As a result, a lot of hotels have not done as much promotion.'' Gourmets have always turned up their noses at the competition, insisting grouse should hang for four r five days to bring out their true gamey taste. The Ritz Hotel in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s Piccadilly area said grouse would be on its menu Friday night for about $ 60 a plate, but `` it will be at its best next week.'' `` Most of our clients prefer it after its been hung for about a week,'' a spokeswoman said. Passengers on <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Air </PERSON>'s 6:50 a.m. flight from <LOCATION> Inverness </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> were among the first to taste this year's grouse. Grouse shot on a Scottish estate before dawn was cooked at the Golsview Hotel in <LOCATION> Nairn </LOCATION>, driven to <LOCATION> Inverness </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> four miles away and served on board. The palatial Gleneagles Hotel in eastern <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, traditionally one of the front-runners in the grouse-serving race, abstained for the fourth successive year because of the serious grouse decline, said general manager <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Lederer </PERSON>. `` We feel we should do everything possible to preserve <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s great sporting traditions in the interests of tourism as a whole and for environmental and ecological reasons in particular,'' he said. <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s Game Conservancy says the grouse population has fallen steadily since the mid-1970s because of disease and because their native habitats have been taken over as farmland. Grouse hunting is particularly popular among <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s landed gentry, and estate owners charge foreign tourists several hundred dollars a day to shoot on their land. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheard </PERSON>, agent for the Duke of <ORGANIZATION> Devonshire </ORGANIZATION>'s northern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> estate at <LOCATION> Bolton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Abbey </LOCATION>, said propects for this year's grouse were `` not too good'' because a parasitic worm called the <LOCATION> Strongyle </LOCATION> has weakened the stock. A Conservative lawmaker said the grouse season is also threatened by a <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> proposal which would require that every bird in its member countries be inspected by a veterinarian within 48 hours of death. The proposal is an effort to ensure that wild animals used for food are healthy. The vet would need to remove the feathers and gut the bird, not only delaying its passage to the dinner table but making it impossible to hang game in a traditional way. `` Such an order is fatuous, dictatorial, militaristic, idiotic and totally unacceptable to <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> or to sportsmen or to anybody who has the brains of a grouse,'' said Sir <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Fairbairn </PERSON>, Conservative member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Perth </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Kinross </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>.
