<HEAD>South Africa Considers Signing Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A South African delegation met with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, Soviet and British diplomats Friday about the possibility of subscribing to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty. No details were disclosed. Under the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons, which has been signed by 137 governments since its preparation in 1969, countries without such weapons open their nuclear facilities to inspection by experts from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agency based in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. Of the five acknowledged nuclear powers, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> have signed but <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> have not. Also among the holdouts are countries believed either to possess nuclear weapons or the potential of producing them, including <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. A South African statement said the delegation was led by Foreign Minister <PERSON> Roelof </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> and Energy Minister <PERSON> Danie </PERSON> <PERSON> Steyn </PERSON>. It said discussions covered `` the effect and interpretation of the provisions of the <ORGANIZATION> NPT </ORGANIZATION>,'' a common official reference to the treaty, and `` clarity was sought ... on the rights and privileges which would apply should the Republic of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> accede to the <ORGANIZATION> NPT </ORGANIZATION>.'' The South African <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday delegation would convey <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCAT