<HEAD>Sikh Bombing Kills Seven</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sikh separatists planted three time bombs in two northern cities Friday, killing seven people and injuring at least 37, police said. On Thursday, a gang believed to be upper-class Hindus attacked two neighboring villages in the northeastern state of <LOCATION> Bihar </LOCATION>, killing 11 <ORGANIZATION> Hindu </ORGANIZATION> untouchables, news reports said. A bomb placed on the roof of a state-owned bus went off 20 minutes after the vehicle left the bus terminal at <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION>, killing seven people and injuring 35, said Police Chief Surinder <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Brar </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Jammu </LOCATION>, the winter capital of <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> state, a bomb exploded in a scooter rickshaw, injuring two people, said Police Superintendent D.S. <LOCATION> Salathia </LOCATION>. Sikh militants also were blamed for placing a time bomb in the most popular and crowded shopping center of <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION>, but the device was detected and defused before it detonated. `` Another 15 minutes and it would have exploded,'' said superintendent <PERSON> R.P </PERSON>. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>. He said the device was detected after someone reported seeing a suspicious canister with a watch attached to it. <PERSON> Brar </PERSON> said a bomb exploded on a bus six miles south of <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION> bound for the town of <LOCATION> Shazadpur </LOCATION> in neighboring <LOCATION> Haryana </LOCATION> state. <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION> is the joint capital of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Haryana </LOCATION> states. Sikhs form only 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people but form a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Radicals have been agitating for an independent Sikh homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> since 1982, claiming discrimination by <PERSON> Hindus </PERSON>, who form 80 percent of the population. The separatist campaign has killed 1,680 people this year. `` It was an encounter with death,'' said <PERSON> Yash </PERSON> <PERSON> Bir </PERSON>, a passenger on the bus who suffered burn injuries in the explosion. `` I was unconscious. I do not know who brought me to hospital.'' <PERSON> Bir </PERSON> spoke to reporters from a bed in a <LOCATION> Chandigarh </LOCATION> hospital, where most of the injured were taken. Doctors said five were in serious condition. The victims were not immediately identified. <PERSON> Brar </PERSON> said the bomb was planted on the bus' rooftop luggage carrier. About 70 passengers were in the vehicle. In other parts of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, Sikh militants were blamed for five other killings Thursday night and Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said. At least three victims were Sikhs, the news agency said. The militants have targeted Hindus and moderate Sikhs in their campaign. The Press Trust of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> news agency said at least two people were seriously injured in the attack on untouchables in <LOCATION> Bihar </LOCATION> on Thursday. No arrests were reported, but the killers are suspected to be upper-class Hindus. More than 80 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people are Hindus, who are mainly divided into four castes. Below the castes are the Harijans or untouchables, the lowest group. Caste prejudices have lessened since <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> gained independence in 1947, but divisions are more apparent in <LOCATION> Bihar </LOCATION>, the poorest state in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Prejudices often erupt into violence there because many untouchables have joined Marxist groups that agitate for distribution of land owned by upper-caste Hindus.
