<HEAD>FAA Eyes Mid-1990s Launch for Vertical-Takeoff Aircraft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> plans to accelerate the certification of fixed-wing aircraft capable of taking off and landing vertically so they might be available for civilian use by the mid-1990s, officials said Friday. The so-called tilt-rotor aircraft technology, which is under development by the military, is seen by some aviation industry experts as a key to providing short-haul air transportation in the future. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Adminstrator <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McAtor </PERSON>, one of the government's chief boosters of the technology, told reporters Friday that the potential civilian uses for the tilt-rotor aircraft is virtually limitless. He suggested it would be ideal for short-haul flights in areas ranging from the congested skies of the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to the isolated airfields of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. Other aviation experts, however, suggest that the use of such planes, which are expected to cost at least $ 20 million apiece and carry only 24 to 30 people per flight, would be too high to be economically successful in the near future. The tilt-rotor aircraft is envisioned as being capable of landing and taking off like a helicopter and having a range of more than 300 miles when its rotors are tilted for fixed-wing flight. <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has entered into a memorandum of understanding with the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to share development information on the tilt-rotor aircraft program so that once the military version is developed it may be adapted quickly for civilian use. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials estimated the agreement will shorten the time it takes to certify such a plane for civilian use by as much as