being used extensively by commuter airlines to transport business travelers in areas where capacity at conventional airports is increasingly limited. In the Northeast, says <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Del </PERSON> <PERSON> Balzo </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s regional administrator in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, a tilt-rotor aircraft eventually could take business travelers from downtown <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> to downtown <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in 45 minutes.
