<HEAD>Health Experts Plan Campaign For Preventive Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An international medical conference on Friday declared a campaign against disease that involves training doctors in preventive care rather than waiting for their patients to become ill. `` Man needs more than science alone,'' said a statement issued by the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> after a five-day meeting in the Old College of <ORGANIZATION> Edinburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> The conference was attended by 160 doctors and health specialists and released the Edinburgh Declaration that was adopted unanimously. It said in part that medical educators must produce doctors `` who will promote the health of all people _ not merely deliver curative services to those who can afford it or to those for whom it is readily available.'' `` Thousands suffer and die every day from diseases which are preventable, curable or self-inflicted and millions have no ready access to health care of any kind,'' the declaration said. `` Such facts have produced a mounting concern in medical education about equity in health care, the humane delivery of health services and the cost to society.'' The declaration was supported by representatives of three <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> agencies: the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Children's Fund -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- and the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Development Program. National ministries of health and education, universities and such funding institutions as the <ORGANIZATION> Rockefeller </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Gulbenkian </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON> foundations, and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> helped finance the conference. `` The message from this meeting is quite clear: Urgent reform of medical training is needed in all countries so that doctors involve their patients in keeping themselves well,'' said <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Walton </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Edinburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> psychiatrist and president of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>. He said the steps to reform doctors' training will be monitored by offices in six regions _ <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. With backing from the government-funded <ORGANIZATION> Scottish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, a site for the central office has been offered by the city of <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walton </PERSON> said the central office will have a staff of about eight and an annual budget of $ 289,000. Followup conferences are scheduled in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> next month and <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, at the end of October, he said. `` We want doctors everywhere to concentrate on how to encourage people to take care of themselves,'' said Dr. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> from <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, former head of the center for educational development at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>. `` We want medical graduates to meet the needs of the people and not be content with curing diseases,'' he said. Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> UNICEF </ORGANIZATION>, said more than two thirds of the 14 million deaths of children each year were caused by such diseases as diarrhea, measles, tetanus, whooping cough and respiratory infection, and the victims could have been protected at low cost. <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said 50,000 people die prematurely every day from causes that could be readily prevented. `` We have the technology to dramatically improve the health of people over the next 20 years ... but will medical education play its role?'' <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> asked. <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON>, the mayor of <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION>, told the closing session: `` We do need high-technology medicine, but ordinary people everywhere know what they want: To keep healthy, to feed their families and to have a city system that gives them clean water. I know it will be a battle to get those things, it always has been.''
