 Anti-communist Afghan guerrillas have captured <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION>, a strategic provincial capital in northeastern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, according to an unconfirmed report cited Friday by Western diplomats. The Moslem insurgents, who usually are the first to publicize their takeovers of Afghan towns even when they are temporary, have said nothing about capturing <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> province. <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION>, about 150 miles north of the Afghan capital of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, would be a significant gain for the guerrillas fighting the Soviet-backed government. The city, 40 miles south of the Soviet border on the main highway leading from <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, would be the first Afghan provincial capital the rebels have won in the 10-year war. Most Soviet troops leaving the country under an April 14 U.N.-sponsored withdrawal agreement are taking another road to the border at <LOCATION> Heiratan </LOCATION>, about 100 miles west of <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION>. Soviet troops entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 and have been helping the Marxist government battle the guerrillas. The Soviets agreed to withdraw half their estimated 100,000 troops by Monday under a pullout plan that began May 15 and is to be completed by Feb. 15. State-run Radio <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> said foreign journalists and local Afghans witnessed `` hundreds'' of <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> soldiers cross into the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on Thursday and Friday. The radio reported that a Pakistani national was arrested Thursday for espionage as he carried two explosive devices in the eastern city of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>. The government-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Bakhtar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said the unidentified Pakistani led Afghan army forces to a guerrilla ammunition depot in <LOCATION> Caprahar </LOCATION>, six miles south of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>. Radio <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> also said two Pakistanis were among 70 people killed during a clash between Afghan army troops and U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas in eastern <LOCATION> Logar </LOCATION> province. There was no information on when the fighting occurred. It described the two Pakistanis as `` advisers'' to the guerrillas. <PERSON> Azim </PERSON> <PERSON> Nasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> resistance organization said guerrillas who arrived about 10 days ago from <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> said nothing of the capital's capture or its vulnerability to an imminent guerrilla takeover. The Afghan News Agency, which claims to be a mouthpiece of the seven-party guerrilla alliance but is operated by members of <PERSON> Gulbadin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hezb-e-Islami </ORGANIZATION>, also could not confirm the capture of <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION>. The loose and often fractured resistance alliance is based in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION> in northwest <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. A strategic gain in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s resource-rich north would dampen any hopes the Afghan government might have for the north as a fallback position if it is unable to hold <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. Western diplomats said <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> might have designs on the north after the government began heavy construction in the northern city of <LOCATION> Mazar-e-Sharif </LOCATION>, appointed a deputy prime minister for the north and consolidated its fighting forces under a single command. Afghan insurgents temporarily captured two provincial capitals in southern and eastern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> since the Soviet withdrawal began, but they were pushed back after heavy bombing attacks, Western diplomats said. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which has an estimated 2.5 million Afghan refugees as well as guerrilla headquarters, signed the withdrawal agreement in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> with the Afghan government. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which backs the insurgency, and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> agreed to act as guarantors. The insurgents have said they will ignore the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accord and keep fighting until the government falls. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, <PERSON> Sahabzada </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaqub </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>, said Friday that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is fully committed to the agreement and a political settlement in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. He said Soviet accusations <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> had violated the accord were `` false, motivated and propagandist.'' The Soviets have accused <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> of continuing to channel weapons to the guerrillas. <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> said the accord carries the promise of the complete withdrawal of foreign forces from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, the return of peace and independence and the safe return of refugees.
