 Hollywood gossip broadcaster <PERSON> Jimmie </PERSON> <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON>, whose career spanned <LOCATION> Tinseltown </LOCATION>'s Golden Age and entertained millions of radio listeners, has died at age 89. <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON>, who died Tuesday at <LOCATION> Westlake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Community </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, was considered to be the most acerbic of his contemporaries, who included <PERSON> Louella </PERSON> <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hedda </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopper </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Winchell </PERSON>. His shows featured stories about stars, movie critiques and his trademark sign-off: `` Good night to you ... and you ... and I do mean you!'' At his peak in 1950 <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON> was earning more than $ 250,000 a year and was heard over 486 stations by 40 million people a week. His syndicated gossip column appeared in 360 newspapers. His show featured a four-bell system for rating new films, `` open letters'' to movie stars in which he critiqued their performances and their behavior and `` notes from the little black book.'' <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON> took pride in being disliked by <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> and credited a network of spies for giving him gossip. `` I had secretaries in studios all over town who would supply me with stories for bonuses of $ 25 to $ 100,'' he once said. He wrote his first column in 1920 for the <ORGANIZATION> Hollywood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, a four-page insert to the old <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON> was once a movie extra with ambitions of becoming a star. He first got attention as a publicity man for Famous Players-Lasky, the forerunner of Paramount. Assigned to <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeMille </PERSON>, he reportedly once increased profits for DeMille's films by telling the news media that the movie mogul had loaded his yacht with rifles and was taking it to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to hunt cannibals. <PERSON> Fidler </PERSON> later ran his own talent agency until it was wiped out by the stock market crash of 1929. He returned to public relations and was asked to interview a <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> starlet for the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> radio show `` Hollywood on the Air.'' After more than 2,000 letters poured in praising the effort, he was given his own 15-minute show. He began to cut back his broadcasts in the 1960s but did n't retire from the air until 1983 He is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Kay </PERSON>, three daughters and four grandchildren.
