<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Virus-killing blood cells vary widely from person to person in the way they recognize the AIDS virus and easily lose their memory for the microbe, making an AIDS vaccine very difficult if not impossible, according to new research. Early attempts at making AIDS vaccines have failed to prompt blood cells known as B cells to make antibodies that wipe out the virus. Some experts contend that for a vaccine to work, it must activate the other main branch of the body's immune defenses, the T cells. However, the latest research suggests important obstacles to building a vaccine that rallies T cells to give life-long protection against the many strains of human immunodeficiency virus, which causes AIDS.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Intravenous drug abusers changed their practices after community workers started warning about AIDS, but even users in treatment have immune system troubles that may hinder their fighting off the disease, two studies reported Friday suggest. Researchers also confirmed known links between psychological states and immune system functioning, and suggested it may make a difference with AIDS. The work was presented Friday at the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The change in drug practices is significant because drug users are often thought not responsive to health warnings, said researcher <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Watters </PERSON>. His study, done in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, found users cut back on sharing of hypodermic needles, which can spread the AIDS virus, and cleaned their needles more, as well as increasing their use of condoms for sex.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> legislators worked Friday to pass anti-corruption legislation inspired by an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> investigation that led to guilty verdicts against dozens of county officials, but the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> were not in agreement. The federal investigation into corrupt county purchasing practices has resulted in charges ranging from extortion to mail fraud against 56 supervisors in 25 counties. Of those, 42 have pleaded guilty, six have been convicted, one has been acquitted, one died before going to trial, one died after sentencing, and another was declared mentally incompetent to stand trial. The remaining ones still have charges pending. The state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> prepared Friday to consider its version of a county government reorganization bill, approval of which would require negotiations between that chamber and the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leaders are <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> graduates who could be earning more than $ 100,000 a year. The participants are high school and college students who could be at the beach. Instead, they're working as a sort of urban Peace Corps that organizers hope will set a national example The program, called City Year, is a privately funded community service project. Fifty students ages 18 to 21, from high school dropouts to <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> students, were culled from 150 applicants. They begin their days at 8 a.m. sharp on <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> Common with 20 minutes of calisthenics. If they're late, they do extra exercises. They spend the rest of the day on various projects, battling the summer's searing heat and humidity as well as urban blight.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hunters flocked to the heather-covered moors of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> on Friday, `` The Glorious Twelfth of August'' and the start of the grouse-hunting season popular with landed gentry and wealthy tourists. But the hunters' gunfire was muted by declining stocks of the wild red grouse, due to a parasite and vigorous protesters who drove the birds away with a pre-dawn swoop on three grouse moors. The <ORGANIZATION> Hunt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Saboteurs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which opposes blood sports, said about 300 members beat the hunters to the bushes and rousted the grouse at <LOCATION> Stanhope </LOCATION> and Gunnerside Moors in northern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and in an area near <LOCATION> Muirshell </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Country </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>.
