<FIRST>a i PM-LordsA-Leaping Adv17 1stLd-Writethru 08-12 0952</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lords A-Leaping, Adv 17, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0166,0975</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs Aug. 17 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Britain's Lords A-Sleeping Now Lords A-Leaping</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, CORRECTS 19th graf ``But of ... political affiliation'' to
say that ``all but 66 are men'' (sted women).</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's been nearly 80 years since the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lords </ORGANIZATION> stuck one foot in the grave and its enemies began looking ahead to a full burial. Yet this curious collection of princes, bishops, dukes, marquises, earls, viscounts and barons seems to be staging a miraculous deathbed recovery. Not only has the upper house beaten its elected partner, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION>, in the race to be televised, it also is handing legislative defeats to Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> at more than double the rate sustained by any Conservative government since World War II. Those who despair of thwarting Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s radical capitalist reforms in the Commons look increasingly to the Lords, where most seats pass from father to son. The peers, who are not elected and serve for life, can vote against the government with no fear of party discipline. The Lords, top-heavy with conservative landowners, ought to be the natural ally of Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s Conservatives. Yet it is the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, sworn enemy of inherited privilege, that is benefitting most from the Lords' independence of mind. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s 101-seat majority in the 650-member Commons guarantees that bills pass in the lower chamber. But in the Lords she has suffered 127 defeats since coming to office in 1979. In recent years the peers have opposed the abolition of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s left-wing local government, rescued free eye and dental checkups, restored free school transport in rural areas, stopped corporal punishment in state schools, toned down a bill to abolish university tenure, curbed the expansion of police stop-and-search powers The Commons still has the last word, and some measures, including abolition of the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> authority, ultimately become law despite the Lords' resistance, but almost always with compromise amendments. `` By and large the two houses have learned to live with each other and the broad effect is that a lot of amendments made by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lords </ORGANIZATION> get accepted by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION>,'' says <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Belstead </PERSON>, the Lords' Conservative leader. Lords-watchers now are divided into two camps: those who say a house based on inherited privilege is bad, and those who say it's bad but ... <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, a columnist in the left-leaning Guardian newspaper, says the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lords </ORGANIZATION> relieves pressure for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to have an elected upper chamber, like the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> `` It is proof that of all the democracies, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is the most backward,'' argues Young. Lord <PERSON> Ponsonby </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s chief whip, calls the hereditary principle `` an intolerable affront to democracy.'' But <PERSON> Ponsonby </PERSON>, himself a peer by inheritance, values the Lords as a revising chamber where Commons' legislation is fine-tuned, and he acknowledges that the Lords today is `` the best ally of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in the legislative process.'' Although the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lords </ORGANIZATION> lost the right to make tax laws in the 17th century, only in 1910 was it stripped of all power over money bills and limited to two years the time period in which it could delay a bill. The emasculation followed the Lords' veto of <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> LLoyd </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON>'s liberal `` budget for the people,'' and most assumed that the Lords, having thrown their reactionary weight about once too often, would soon be scrapped altogether. Their power to delay a bill was cut to one year in 1949. The creation of new peers remains a potent tool of government patronage. <PERSON> Belstead </PERSON> maintains the Lords has opened up to new walks of life _ actors, small businessmen, trade unionists, and women. But of the 1,191 peers, 759 are there by inheritance, only 10 of them Laborites. All but four are white, all but 66 are men, and 446 are Conservatives to <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s 117 and the centrist parties' 87. The remainder are independents or declare no political affiliation. Only about 300 peers attend debates regularly, and in May the government had to summon non-attenders to ensure passage of a controversial property tax bill. The turnout of 509 was the second biggest this century. The key to Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s defeats have been regular attenders among the 266 independents, the `` crossbenchers.'' <PERSON> Belstead </PERSON>, 55, a lanky former schoolteacher who inherited his father's title in 1958, has no ready answer to why the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> survives. In an interview, he focused on the Lords' function as a revising chamber, noting that peers work long hours and draw only 52-pounds -LRB- $ 88 -RRB- for each session attended, plus expenses. The chamber also provides the Law Lords, nine ennobled judges who sit as the country's highest court. Although they treasure their archaic rituals, the Lords boast of an openness to change. They brought in electric lights before the Commons, and have allowed their debates to be televised since 1984, something the Commons only now is planning. All in all, it's a relaxed place. It's still quite acceptable to fall asleep in mid-speech _ the giveaway is often the ear trumpet sliding out of the hand _ or to ramble on at length about grouse-shooting, leaky army boots, and what to do if Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> is at the hairdresser's during a nuclear alert. And then there's the joy of dressing up in ermine gowns and two-peaked hats to welcome a new member. `` For one day of the year I was even prettier than my wife,'' remarked <PERSON> Len </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> when he went from being general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> national </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> federation </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, to being Lord <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Epping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs Aug. 17</NOTE>
