<HEAD>GOP Convention Bandleader Ready for Any of 12 VP Candidates</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Like others at the 1980 Republican national convention, orchestra leader <PERSON> Manny </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> was nervously awaiting announcement of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s choice for vice presidential running mate. Rumors persisted that former President <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> would get the nod. For journalists, that meant getting copy ready on the former <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> congressman. For political power brokers and analysts, it meant consideration of the impact of a Reagan-Ford ticket. For <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, who once again this week serves as musical director at the Republican Convention in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, it meant making sure his musicians had sheet music ready for `` The <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Fight Song'' and `` You've Got to Be a Football Hero.'' `` All of a sudden <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> came out of the woodwork and everyone got caught short,'' <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> recalled. `` I could n't think of where <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was from. I knew it was a couple of places -LRB- <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> -RRB-. `` Then someone remembered that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> went to <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> said. Ah, an <ORGANIZATION> Ivy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leaguer </ORGANIZATION>. Sheet music out, ladies and gentlemen, for `` Boola Boola.'' Once again, <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, now 78, saved the musical day. `` We just got lucky on that one,'' he said. <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> is playing the vice presidential blues this year on the downbeat of certain Republican presidential nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, in a recent telephone interview from his office, said he has identified at least 12 possible candidates from news accounts. And everyone has to have a song. <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> may have only minutes from learning the name to playing an introductory tune for the nominee. He has a 700-song library to choose from. `` We try to figure out beforehand where the candidates are from,'' said <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>. `` I know some of the different candidates from playing for them at various functions, and I know certain tunes they like. And there are a lot of tunes that still have fire to them but are n't regional,'' he said. That's important, because sometimes the official state tune is n't necessarily the one that a crowd recognizes, or likes. For the record, noted <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, the official state song of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> is `` I Love You, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>,'' not `` <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, Here I Come.'' and for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, it's `` The Great Big State of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' not `` East Side, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>.'' And folks are sensitive about that type of thing, <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> has learned. `` I once got called out on the carpet for playing ` East Side, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>' for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' he said. His compromise in such cases is a two-song medley, with the less popular but official tune giving way to the more well-known number. <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> also has noted over the years a shift in the role of the orchestra at the convention. The orchestra once was used as a device to bring unruly crowds under control with the irresistible beat of a patriotic tune. Modern conventions, slickly produced and geared for television, have fewer and fewer items settled by floor fights. They depend more upon great sound, spectacles and split-second timing, he said. What's lost is the drama. `` Once in 1968 in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, there was a floor fight,'' said <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, who could not recall what the fight was over. `` Then it turned into a real demonstration, and things started to get out of hand, -LRB- <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Senator -RRB- <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said, ` Play something patriotic!' `` We played ` God Bless <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,' and everybody had to stand up,'' <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> said. `` But we had to play it three times before everybody calmed down.'' <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> is a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> native who has spent more than 50 years in the music business, including 17 with <ORGANIZATION> RKO </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION>, where he scored and directed music for feature films. He also befriended <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, then a song-and-dance man for the studio. As the leader of the <LOCATION> Cocoanut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orchestra </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> became a favorite of Hollywood stars and worked on several films. He also became one of the movie colony's most sought-after orchestra leaders for benefits and galas. <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>'s first gig as <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> bandmaster was in 1956, when <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> carried the party's banner for a second term, along with Vice President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>. A 50-piece orchestra played at that Cow Palace convention in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> will bring 12 musicians to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> and pick 10 more union musicans from that city's ample roster. `` Everybody's on a budget now,'' he said with a laugh. <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, who has also directed orchestras at several <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> functions, has declined over the years to reveal his political affiliation. He has played music at various functions for every American president since <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> liked foxtrots, he recalled. `` He and Mrs. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> used to throw a lot of parties,'' said <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>. `` They were always formal.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: <ORGANIZATION> PURCELL </ORGANIZATION> IS BACK _ <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Purcell </PERSON>, who served as an interviewer for six seasons on `` Real People,'' will be host a new, hour-long syndicated show called `` Public People, Private Lives.'' Premiering Oct. 1 in about 80 percent of the country's TV markets, the program will feature well-known personalities from all walks of life.
