<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks have boosted the prime lending rate back into the double digits for the first time in three years, reflecting the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s drive to push all interest rates higher to stave off inflation. Thursday's half-percentage point hike in the prime, to 10 percent, pushed the lending rate to its highest level since the spring of 1985. The increase is likely to pinch the pocketbooks of consumers who already have seen borrowing costs rise in recent months.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Commending `` the indomitable spirit'' of drought-stricken farmers, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has signed the nation's largest-ever disaster relief bill. Also on Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said new surveys point to a drought-damaged corn crop this fall of 4.48 billion bushels, down 37 percent from last year's harvest and the smallest output since 1983. Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly lower on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>.
