<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Bally </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> says it plans to spin off its hotel-casino group, which accounts for nearly half of its revenue, as a separate publicly-held company but will retain up to a 15 percent stake in the business. <ORGANIZATION> Bally </ORGANIZATION> stockholders will receive, tax-free, one share of common stock in the hotel-casino business for each share of <ORGANIZATION> Bally </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> they own on the effective date of the spin-off, the Chicago-based company stated Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Bally </ORGANIZATION> will retain all components of its leisure and manufacturing businesses, including its chains of fitness centers and video arcades and its gaming and exercise equipment businesses.
