 A federal judge has upheld a landmark patent ruling in favor of <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, saying another judge in the case against <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was unbiased even though a relative owned <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> stock. `` Under the circumstances, I can not find that it is the law that <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> obtain a vacation of this case up to this point,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON> said Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> had asked <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON> to throw out a 1985 decision by another federal judge that <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> had violated several Polaroid patents on instant film and cameras.
