<HEAD>Banks Quickly Follow Fed In Boosting Interest Rates</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY37 of Aug. 11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Businesses and consumers with bank loans priced according to swings in the prime interest rate will feel the most immediate impact from major banks' decisions to boost the rate for the third time this year. The banks raised their base lending rates by a half-percentage point to 10 percent on Thursday _ a more than 3-year high _ in reaction to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s drive to push all interest rates higher to curb inflation. The prime rate increase, the second in a month, puts the key lending rate in double-digit territory for the first time since June 1985. Because the prime is used to calculate a wide range of fixed-and adjustable-rate loans, the change will affect consumers who already have seen borrowing costs rise in recent months. A higher prime rate will affect small - to medium-sized businesses and consumers more so than large corporations, which borrow more cheaply in the open market by issuing commercial paper, or short-term unsecured IOUs Home equity lines of credit usually are pegged to the prime rate, while many adjustable-rate home mortgages are tied to interest paid on <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reiners </PERSON>, an economist at <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said higher borrowing costs may have a significant effect on the spending habits of consumers, who have been buying on credit in increasing numbers lately. `` If you have to pay more -LRB- for loans -RRB- then you have less money to buy things like furniture, clothing ... and other little niceties,'' she said. `` It will slow the economy, but it wo n't stop it in its tracks,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>, chief financial economist for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. International `` That's a healthy thing right now. `` You try to get your flu shot before you get the flu ... That's preventative medicine That's what the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is doing,'' <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON> said. Financial markets took Thursday's news in stride after weathering the storm that followed the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s increase in a key lending rate earlier in the week. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed up 5.16 to 2,039.30. Bond prices, which generally decline in the face of rising interest rates, ended mixed. The dollar lost ground against all key foreign currencies, although some European traders credited the prime rate hike for preventing a free fall. <ORGANIZATION> Chase </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> was the first to announce the prime hike Thursday morning, with other major banks across the country quickly following suit. The increase brings the prime to its highest level since June 18, 1985, when it was lowered to 9.5 percent from 10 percent. The prime was at 8.5 percent at the beginning of the year. The banks raised it to 9 percent on May 11 and then to 9.5 percent on July 14. Economists widely had anticipated the latest boost the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> signaled its desire to tighten credit on Tuesday by raising its discount rate to 6.5 percent from 6 percent, citing inflationary pressures. The discount rate is the interest the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> charges on loans to member banks. Economists said the subsequent boost in the prime reflected the rising of borrowing costs faced by the banks. Rates banks pay on products such as certificates of deposits or money market accounts have been forced up, although not at the same pace as bank loans. The trend toward higher interest rates reflects prevailing concerns in the credit markets that the economy might be overheating and inflation creeping up. Higher inflation erodes the value of fixed-rate investments such as <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds, forcing borrowers to pay higher interest rates to attract investors. Many analysts predict interest rate will continue to head higher but discount a big increase.
</TEXT>
