<HEAD>Judge Upholds Out Patent Case Decisions in Polaroid Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s patent court victory over rival <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was upheld by a federal judge, who ruled that another judge in the case was unbiased despite a relative's <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> stock holdings. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON> on Thursday rejected <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s request to throw out a 1985 decision by another federal judge who found <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> had violated several Polaroid patents on instant film and cameras. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlton </PERSON> immediately appealed the decision to the 1st <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON>'s ruling came during the first hearing to set a schedule for the damages portion of the case. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> has requested $ 5.7 billion in damages for the patent infringements. The damages trial tentatively is set to begin in January. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> had argued in the 12-year-old patent case that all of federal Judge <PERSON> Rya </PERSON> <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON>'s rulings in the case should be vacated because <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON>'s mother-in-law owned 1,000 shares of <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> stock worth about $ 100,000 when the trial began in 1981. <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON> withdrew from the case in June shortly after her mother-in-law died and she was named as a beneficiary of the stock, which had increased to 2,150 shares because of stock splits. `` Under the circumstances, I can not find that it is the law that <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> obtain a vacation of this case up to this point,'' <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON> said. `` I do not think that would be fair or be equitable to everyone.'' <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON> said <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON> made it clear at the outset of the trial in October 1981 that her mother-in-law owned the <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> stock. He said neither <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> nor <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> raised the issue during the initial trial, after <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON>'s ruling in 1985 or during a lengthy appeal process. `` She said she did not think that was a disqualifying reason,'' <PERSON> Mazzone </PERSON> said, `` I do n't think that was incorrect. <PERSON> Eastman </PERSON> <PERSON> Kodak </PERSON> did not disagree with it.'' <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> called the decision `` entirely proper and correct and obviously sound.'' Polaroid, the Cambridge-based camera company that pioneered instant photography, sued <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> in 1976 after the <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, camera company introduced its own line of instant film and cameras. <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON> ruled in September 1985 that <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> had infringed on seven of about 150 Polaroid patents, and barred <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> from the business in January 1986. On May 9, she told both sides that she intended to remove herself from the case because she and her husband were beneficiaries of her mother-in-law's estate. The judge acquiesced after both sides encouraged her to continue in the case and asked her for time to research the situation. But in a motion filed June 15, <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> called for <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON>'s immediate disqualification and dismissal of all her rulings in the case since October 1981 One week later, she withdrew.
