<HEAD>London Shares Higher At Midday On Cautious Bargain-Hunting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices were higher at midday Friday, as players cautiously stepped in to pick up some bargains after sharp declines earlier in the week. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 8.3 points, or 0.5 percent, at 1,843.5 at about 12:15 p.m. The index moved up as much as 10.9 points in late morning. Volume was moderate at 244.3 million shares at midday compared with 270.3 million shares at the same time Thursday. While gains were widespread, institutional buying focused on selected shares. In particular, buying was seen in those stocks that had suffered the most from the week's declines, triggered by interest rate rises in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> earlier in the week. Fund managers, still sitting on large cash reserves, appeared unwilling to miss out should equities begin to rally in coming weeks. Many had expected the 100-share index to rise above 1,900 last week, before interest rates were pushed higher. `` They -LRB- institutions -RRB- do n't really want to be sellers,'' an equity salesman said. `` There is a fear of having too much cash'' in institutional portfolios.
