<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Shows Inflation On The Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with six grafs to UPDATE with report on wholesale
prices; will be led with Commerce Department report on business
inventories and sales during June, due at 10 a.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Inflation at the wholesale level rose to an annual rate of 5.7 percent in July, reflecting big boosts in a wide variety of products, including clothng, automobiles, furniture and poultry, the government said today. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that wholesale prices rose 0.5 percent last month, the biggest gain since March. Price increases were widespread across a wide variety of non-food items, such as drugs, which were up 1.1 percent and cosmetics, up 1.7 percent. In June, the department's Producer Price Index for finised goods rose 0.4 percent, or at an annual rate of 4.6 percent, more than double the 2.2 percent rate of wholesale price inflation for all of 1987. Today's report comes just three days after the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> initiated an increase in interest rates to fight inflation. On Thursday, major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks reacted quickly to the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s move by boosting the prime lending rate a half percentage point to 10 percent, the highest level since the spring of 1985. The prime rate hike, though, did n't upset the financial markets because it was a widely expected response to the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s earlier action, in which the central bank raised the discount rate half a percentage point to 6.5 percent. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.16 Thursday to 2,039.30. The average had had fallen nearly 100 points over the five previous sessions, partly because of interest-rate jitters. The dollar lost ground against all key foreign currencies, indicating that the boost in the prime rate was not seen as a powerful lure for foreign money. The dollar's weakness in turn hurt bond prices, which finished mostly unchanged or lower. Because the prime is used to calculate a wide range of fixed-and adjustable-rate loans, the increase is likely to pinch the pocketbooks of consumers who already have seen borrowing costs rise in recent months. `` It will slow the economy, but it wo n't stop it in its tracks,'' explained <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>, chief financial economist for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. International `` That's a healthy thing right now. `` You try to get your flu shot before you get the flu ... That's preventative medicine That's what the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is doing.'' The increase brings the closely watched rate to its highest level since June 18, 1985, when it was lowered to 9.5 percent from 10 percent. At the start of the year, the prime stood at 8.5 percent. It was raised to 9 percent on May 11 and then another half percentage point on July 14. The trend toward higher interest rates reflects prevailing concerns in the credit markets that the economy might be overheating and inflation creeping up. In indicator of economic activity, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that retail sales climbed 0.5 percent in July. But economists warned that rising interest rates threaten to dampen even this modest growth rate in the months ahead.
</TEXT>
