<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> said delays in scheduled European flights in June were at least three times as many as in June 1986. <ORGANIZATION> AEA </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Karl-Heinz </PERSON> <PERSON> Neumeister </PERSON> said Friday that while delays in scheduled flights are not yet as bad as for charter flights, `` the situation is definitely getting worse.'' In January, 11.5 percent of scheduled flights in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> were more than 15 minutes late and by late June, this had reached 22 percent, <PERSON> Neumeister </PERSON> said in a statement. `` In June 1988, the delays caused by congestion problems were more than three times as many as in June 1986,'' he said. In reality, he said, the picture is even worse since AEA on-time figures do not include `` reactionary delays'' where inbound flights, late due to insufficient air traffic control capacity, delay outgoing flights. Normally, flight punctuality drops during the winter months because of weather conditions and rises in the summer. `` In 1988, the trend was reversed,'' <PERSON> Neumeister </PERSON> said. He blamed this uncharacteristic drop on insufficient air traffic control capacity. In recent months, thousands of European vacationers have spent long hours at airports as their south-bound charters were delayed by strikes by air traffic controllers in several countries.
