 Corn, oat and soybean futures soared their permitted limits at today's opening on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in reaction to the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s assessment of the drought's toll on crop production. In a report issued after the markets closed on Thursday, The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> predicted this year's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn production would fall 37 percent below last year's harvest, soybean production would decline by 23 percent and wheat production would drop by 14 percent. Analysts said the government's soybean production estimate of 1.47 billion bushels _ the smallest harvest since 1976 _ was the biggest surprise. `` The market must work higher to seek a price that will discourage usage or we're simply going to run out of soybeans, and the market wo n't let that happen,'' said <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Feltes </PERSON>, director of commodties research for <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a Chicago-based commodity brokerage house. Corn and oat futures are limited to daily moves of 10 cents a bushel and soybeans to 30 cents a bushel. The exchange has removed the limits on the soybean contract for August delivery, which leaped more than 50 cents a bushel at the opening. In early trading, wheat was 9 -LCB- cents to 10 cents higher with the contract for delivery in September at $ 3.92 a bushel; corn was 5 -RCB- cents to 10 cents higher with September at $ 3.06 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 10 cents higher across the board with September at $ 2.84 -LCB- a bushel; and soybeans were 30 cents to 59 cents higher with August at $ 9.15 a bushel. Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .30 cent lower to .58 cent higher with August at 68.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .37 cent to .60 cent lower with August at 80.30 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to 1 cent higher with August at 46.80 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .68 cent to 1.93 cent higher with August at 36.40 cents a pound. Cattle futures settled lower on Thursday while pork futures were higher.
