<SECOND>AM-Store Cards, Bjt,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Considers Deregulating Some Interest Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s retail stores would be able to charge unlimited interest rates on their credit-card accounts under legislation being considered by Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON>. The proposal, supported by the retailers but opposed by consumer groups, would repeal during a three-year period the current 18 percent interest ceiling that was established 28 years ago. Bank credit cards would not be affected. Democratic state Sen. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Dills </PERSON>, who introduced the bill, said current limit prevents stores from offering credit to poorer consumers. The no-limit interest policy would `` open up some credit opportunities that do n't exist at this time,'' added Democratic Assemblyman <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON>. But critics charge the proposal would result in $ 450 million in additional interest charges over three years. <PERSON> Assemblyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Connelly </PERSON>, a Democrat, described the measure as `` clearly the worst consumer bill of the year.'' He said <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> consumers pay an extra $ 50 million in interest rates for each percentage point added to interest rates by stores. <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON>, in 1982, 1984 and 1986, approved temporary increases in the interest limit to 19.2 percent. However, last year the governor vetoed another increase, noting that the prime lending rate had fallen from over 20 percent in 1980 to between 8 percent and 9 percent in 1987, and `` the record is devoid of evidence supporting the need for the higher ceiling.'' <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON>, who rarely discusses pending legislation, has declined to discuss his position on the bill. He has until the end of this month to decide its fate. The Assembly approved the bill in a 49-22 vote Monday; the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed it in June. The bill would take effect Jan. 1, 1989 and expire three years later, at which time the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> could decide to extend or kill it based on a review by a non-partisan state legislative analyst. Assemblyman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, a Republican who was a key backer of the bill, said that if stores are limited to 18 percent they can offer credit only to customers considered lower risks or raise their prices to compensate for the loss. The current ceiling `` is hurting <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> consumers as well as the retail industry,'' <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> said. Deregulation would `` let the marketplace set the rates.'' Democratic Assemblyman <PERSON> Rusty </PERSON> <PERSON> Aerias </PERSON>, a critic of the bill, said that a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> study found that stores actually did not offer poor people more credit after deregulation. `` This is a reverse <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hood </PERSON> where we're robbing from the poor,'' he said. According to an Assembly finance committee, 16 other states have deregulated retail credit.
</TEXT>
