<FIRST>a f BC-ChipOutlook Adv15   08-12 1163</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Chip Outlook, Adv 15,1199</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Aug. 15</NOTE>
<HEAD>Semiconductors Prices Are Down, But Electronics Makers Still Worry</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY26 of Aug. 11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A severe shortage of computer memory chips is slowly beginning to ease, but <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electronics makers remain deeply concerned about their vulnerability to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s control of the critical components. Memory chips are the plywood of the worldwide electronics industry _ essential to products ranging from personal computers to copying machines. The supply crunch has left <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electronics makers wringing their hands over lost sales, foregone profits, delayed product introductions and worsened relations with customers. Although Japanese companies such as <ORGANIZATION> NEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> account for 80 to 90 percent of worldwide sales of memory chips, few people are accusing those companies of delibrately engineering the shortages. In fact, there is a shortage of memory chips inside <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, which has surpassed the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to become the world's largest consumer of chips. `` Some major, major major corporations in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> ca n't find product. They're coming to us,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gurewitz </PERSON>, an owner of <ORGANIZATION> H </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; R Enterprises in <LOCATION> Canoga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, which deals in used and surplus chips. Nevertheless, the vulnerability of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies to Japanese suppliers has been highlighted by the chip squeeze. The dominance in memory chips gives the Japanese a base to solidify control of the products that use the chips. `` The Japanese have a large stake in supplanting -LRB- U.S.-based -RRB- merchant producers as the providers of leading-edge chip technologies,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Borrus </PERSON>, deputy director of the <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Roundtable </LOCATION> on the International Economy. If the Japanese companies succeed in gaining unquestioned leadership in chip technology, they will be able to reserve the latest chips for their own computers, phone switches, satellites and other equipment before making them available to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and European rivals, <PERSON> Borrus </PERSON> said. `` At stake for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy is not simply the $ 25 billion market for semiconductors, but the current $ 0.5 trillion market for the final products that incorporate semiconductors, soon to be a $ 1 trillion market,'' <PERSON> Borrus </PERSON> writes in a new book, `` Competing for Control: <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Stake in Microelectronics.'' So far the threat from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is more theoretical than real. For example, <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION>, the world's biggest producer of 1-megabit DRAMs -LRB- pronounced dee-rams -RRB-, allocates more than 60 percent of its output of the chips to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> customers even though its own personal computer unit in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is short on them. But the potential for manipulation is starkly obvious, especially considering that DRAMs can account for up to a quarter of the cost of building a computer. <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microsystems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is one company that has felt the sting of the chip shortage. The booming <LOCATION> Silicon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> maker of computer workstations, which just cracked the $ 1 billion barrier in annual sales, says its revenue would have been $ 100 million higher if chip shortages had not delayed deliveries. Sun occupies a market that Japanese competitors have scarcely touched, yet is heavily dependent on chips from companies that are potential rivals. A similar dilemma faces another <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> computer industry star, <ORGANIZATION> Cray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which relies on Japanese-made chips at the same time it fends off Japanese challenges to its role as the world's leading maker of supercomputers <ORGANIZATION> Cray </ORGANIZATION> has never taken a position on whether a strong, U.S.-based semiconductor industry is needed. Ironically, for all the problems of a chip shortage, the greatest long-term danger to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electronics industry could come from an eventual chip glut. The last glut drove several of the biggest U.S.-based DRAM suppliers out of the business because they could not afford the huge losses, and the next one could wreak similar havoc. Japanese companies are better able to sustain losses on chips because they make other products that tide them over. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, only <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is in a similar position. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> is the world's largest DRAM producer, but sells none to outsiders. The only two U.S.-based companies that still sell DRAMs on the open market are <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Micron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which have earned windfall profits that will enable them to keep current on the technology. For now, a bust in memory chip prices is still a distant threat. <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION>, in a statement prepared for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, said `` we are afraid that the current unusual supply-demand relations will not ease until the middle of 1989.'' Shortages of the older 256-kilobit DRAMs could prevail even longer because production lines for them have been retooled for the new chips. There are also growing shortages of 1-megabit static random access memories, or SRAMs. Average <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spot prices have fallen to $ 37 apiece in July from $ 47.50 in April for the most advanced memory chips in mass production, the 1 million-bit dynamic random access memories known as 1-megabit DRAMs. That is still way above the $ 19.50 spot price that prevailed in July 1987, according to <ORGANIZATION> Dataquest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the market research firm. In April, some desperate customers paid as much as $ 65 apiece for small quantities of 1-megabit DRAMs, according to <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Giudice </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Dataquest </ORGANIZATION>. It became common for companies to pillage memory chips from older computers and other equipment. The supply squeeze in memory chips seems to have two main sources, the main one being the sticky transition to the new, hard-to-build megabit chips from the older 256-kilobit variety. Producing the new chips demands unprecedented precision and cleanliness, and it has taken chipmakers longer than expected to gear up production. At the same time, a boom in sales of personal computers and other gear has increased the demand for the chips. A secondary reason for the squeeze is the 1986 accord between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to prevent `` dumping'' of Japanese-made chips at unfairly low prices. In order to prop up prices to comply with the accord, the Japanese government instructed its chip makers to hold back on production. That anti-dumping accord was supposed to lure more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies back into producing DRAMs by guaranteeing them some protection when chip prices begin skidding, an inevitable process given the improving yields from existing fabrication lines and the start-up of new ones. So far, though, few companies have been lured back. <ORGANIZATION> Motorola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is starting up DRAM production again. But <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, in spite of the accord, dropped out of the DRAM business last year. The reluctance of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies to enter or stay in the market is understandable considering the roughly $ 300 million it takes to build a state-of-the-art fabrication plant and the boom-bust nature of chip prices. In the long run, many analysts say, sustaining a healthy chip industry in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will probably depend on more government initiatives such as the anti-dumping accord and _ importantly _ closer cooperation between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> chipmakers and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> chip users. `` We're both realizing that adversarial is n't the best way to go,'' said <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Victor </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> spokesman.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Aug. 15</NOTE>
