<HEAD>Audi Mulls Options in Sudden Acceleration Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Car owners involved in a lawsuit alleging some of <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s cars are defective are forming a `` barricuda network'' to attack the company after a judge threw out a tentative settlement, a company official contended Friday. Cook County Circuit Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> on Thursday threw out the proposed settlement between the company and a class of <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> car owners who alleged that <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> 5000 sedans suddenly accelerate without warning. `` I sense a barricuda network setting up where everybody wants to get a piece of the meat and to get into the deep pockets of <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, of which Troy, Mich.-based <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> is a subsidiary. <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION> contended Friday that the <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Victims </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, a group of <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> car owners based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, was advising some of its members to withdraw from the class-action lawsuit and file individual lawsuits against the company. Such a move could cost the company thousands of dollars in legal fees, he said. <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said only 1,500 of the 340,000 owners of the <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> sedans covered by the proposed settlement of the class-action lawsuit refused to agree to it. He blamed the settlement's rejection on the victims network `` The <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Victims </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> has not been a headache to us, it's been a major disease to <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Nassau </PERSON>, an attorney for the victims network, said he had advised his clients to withdraw from the class-action suit because, under terms of the proposed settlement, owners would have had to buy another <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION>. The group of about 800 <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> owners contend their cars suddenly accelerate without warning, <PERSON> Nassau </PERSON> said. `` Some people have put their cars away and refuse to drive or sell them,'' he said. `` Why would they want to buy another one? `` I would say if we were barricudas, there must be sharks circling in the waters as well,'' he said, referring to <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> officials trying to eliminate complaints from car owners. The case stems from a 1987 class-action lawsuit alleging that <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> 5000s were defective because of sudden acceleration problems. The settlement would have applied to owners of <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> 5000s built between 1978 and 1986. <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> officials maintain that owners have been unable to prove their <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> 5000 sedans have any defects and say the settlement rejected by <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> is fair. Under terms of the settlement, proposed in June by attorneys for both sides, <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> car owners who bought another <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> would have been offered rebates of up to $ 2,000, but would have had to free the company from all liability. The judge recommended Thursday that both sides try to negotiate a new settlement and report any progress at a hearing scheduled for Aug. 31. `` After the ruling, we have to look at all our options,'' <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said. `` One option is to renegotiate; the other is to litigate.'' <PERSON> Nassau </PERSON> said the victims network may ask the judge to let them become a third party in the case. `` There's no question that we're going to be watching to see what happens next,'' <PERSON> Nassau </PERSON> said a day after <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> approved his motion to throw out a previous judge's ruling giving preliminary approval to the settlement. <PERSON> Nassau </PERSON>'s motion called for vacating Circuit Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON>'s earlier ruling, contending the judge had not given `` proper scrutiny'' to the matter before approving it. After giving the proposed settlement the preliminary go-ahead, <PERSON> Siegan </PERSON> removed himself from the case in July, saying he had a potential conflict of interest because he was friends with an attorney in the case. Thursday's ruling was a victory for the Center for Auto Safety, a Washington-based group formed by consumer activist <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON>. The center contended that the <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> acceleration problem was linked to at least 1,650 accidents, causing 402 injuries and five deaths.
