<HEAD>Bond Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices declined moderately Friday, rounding out a traumatic week of steep losses that catapulted interest rates to their highest levels this year. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s closely watched 30-year bond fell about -RRB- point, or $ 3.75 for every $ 1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves inversely to its price and is often an indicator of interest rate trends, rose to 9.42 percent from 9.38 percent late Thursday. The yield on the 30-year bond has not been this high since Dec. 11, 1987, when it reached 9.44 percent. Bond prices took a beating this week after the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> raised its discount rate on Tuesday. The increase in the discount rate, the interest the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> charges on loans to major financial institutions, was the first such hike since last October's stock market crash. A rise in interest rates sends bond prices lower. The central bank raised the discount rate a half-percentage point, to 6.5 percent, to stem inflationary pressure on the economy. Many market watchers had expected the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to tighten its reins on the money supply _ but few were anticipating that dramatic a move. `` It's just been a lousy week,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Mitchell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Held </ORGANIZATION>, chief financial economist for <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. He suggested that Friday's more tempered decline in bond values was caused by a residue of negative sentiment from the week. The yield on the key 30-year issue jumped from 9.10 percent on Monday, the day before the discount-rate hike, to Friday's 9.42 percent. In the secondary market for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds Friday, prices of short-term government issues were unchanged to 1-32 point lower, intermediate maturities slipped 5-32 point to 3-16 point, and 20-year issues lost 5-32 point, according to figures provided by <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a financial information service. The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $ 10 in the price of a bond with a $ 1,000 face value. The <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Bond Index, which measures price movements on all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues with maturities of a year or longer, edged up 0.67 to 1,126.55. Corporate bonds were slightly lower. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, slipped 0.02 to 280.28. Three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, meanwhile, edged up 1 basis point to a discounted rate of 7.00 percent and a yield of 7.21 percent. Six-month bills rose 3 basis points to a discounted rate of 7.45 percent to yield 7.84 percent while one-year bills were up 1 basis point at 7.65 percent to yield 8.21 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield is the annualized return on an investment in a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill. The discounted rate is the interest rate the market uses to price bills. The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was quoted late in the day at 8 -LRB- percent, up from 8 1-16 percent late Thursday.
