<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 July's hot weather cost Americans over a quarter-billion dollars more than normal in keeping cool, the government has reported. The national air conditioning bill for July was $ 4.3 billion, some $ 255 million more than would have been expected in normal weather, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. That averaged out to a July air conditioning bill of $ 104 for the typical home, $ 6 more than normal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five top officers of the investment group <ORGANIZATION> Princeton-Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> have pleaded innocent to racketeering charges, and their lawyers criticized what they called a `` broad attack on Wall Street.'' A sixth defendant was not present at Thursday's arraignment at federal court in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, but his lawyer entered an innocent plea for him. All six were named last week in a 35-count indictment on charges of racketeering and conspiracy, the first time a racketeering charge has been leveled against securities traders.
