<HEAD>GM Raises Prices on 1989 Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it will raise prices of its 1989 automobiles an average of 2.9 percent because of higher manufacturing costs. New prices announced by <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stempel </PERSON> include increases up to 4.6 percent for the redesigned, larger 1989 <ORGANIZATION> Cadillac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sedan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> DeVille </ORGANIZATION>, and more than 5 percent from current discounted levels for the popular <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corsica </ORGANIZATION> four-door sedan. Prices of some cars, including <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s most expensive, the $ 56,533 <ORGANIZATION> Cadillac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allante </ORGANIZATION>, and its least expensive, the $ 6,399 <ORGANIZATION> Pontiac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LeMans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coupe </ORGANIZATION>, will be unchanged, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> Comptroller <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhame </PERSON> said. However, <PERSON> Stempel </PERSON> said, discounts on options have cut prices of some models enough so that even with the increases, their 1989 introductory prices will be down from a year earlier. `` For example, the 1989 introductory prices for the <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corsica </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Beretta </LOCATION>, two of our most popular cars, are on average 4 percent to 5 percent lower than their comparably equipped counterparts at 1988 introductory price levels,'' he said. <PERSON> Rhame </PERSON> said that as an example, the manufacturer's suggested retail price at the start of the 1988 model year for a <LOCATION> Corsica </LOCATION> with options including air conditioning, automatic transmission, tilt wheel, tinted glass, rear window defogger and cruise control was $ 11,618. With options discounts, the price of that car now would be $ 10,618, he said. For 1989 it will be $ 11,168, a 5.2 percent increase, but still down 3.9 percent from the 1988 introductory level. The base price of the <ORGANIZATION> Cadillac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sedan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> DeVille </ORGANIZATION> will rise to $ 25,435 from $ 23,404 for 1988, <PERSON> Rhame </PERSON> said. The high-volume Chevrolet Cavalier 4-door sedan will have a base price of $ 8,595, up from $ 8,195, with the addition of rear-seat shoulder belts as standard equipment for 1989, he said. Base prices will drop on some models, such as the <ORGANIZATION> Oldsmobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cutlass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Calais </ORGANIZATION> two-door coupe, which will start at $ 9,995, down from a 1988 base price of $ 10,320. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s light truck prices will increase an average of 3 percent, <PERSON> Rhame </PERSON> said, although specific truck prices were not released. Earlier this month, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> announced price increases for 1989 ranging from 1.9 percent to 5.3 percent on six of its most popular cars. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> said in late July it will raise 1989 prices an average of 3 percent, with increases up to 9 percent on some popular models such as mini-vans.
